00:11:17.420 --> 00:11:21.200
The first topic we have to
attack is the question of

00:11:21.200 --> 00:11:23.800
what is the immune system
and how does it work?

00:11:23.800 --> 00:11:28.800
I think many of you have heard
of antibodies or killer cells

00:11:28.810 --> 00:11:31.160
or the various organs of
the body that are involved

00:11:31.160 --> 00:11:31.993
in the immune system,

00:11:31.993 --> 00:11:34.110
like the bone marrow,
the spleen, the thymus,

00:11:34.110 --> 00:11:35.253
and the lymph nodes.

00:11:36.300 --> 00:11:39.640
I'd like to just take a
moment and do a sort of

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:43.950
brief immune system 101; really simple,

00:11:43.950 --> 00:11:45.810
cover the basic elements
of the immune system

00:11:45.810 --> 00:11:49.160
so that everyone
listening or watching this

00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:52.700
can get a clear sense of how
the immune system functions

00:11:52.700 --> 00:11:55.200
and what its basic parts are.

00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:57.380
For some of you, this might be too basic.

00:11:57.380 --> 00:11:58.970
It might be a little bit of background

00:11:58.970 --> 00:12:00.000
that you already know.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:02.450
I think for most of you,
this information will be new.

00:12:02.450 --> 00:12:05.380
And I promise you, you
don't need a biology

00:12:05.380 --> 00:12:07.300
or medicine background in
order to understand this.

00:12:07.300 --> 00:12:09.590
It's actually really simple

00:12:09.590 --> 00:12:12.580
because it is truly elegant in design.

00:12:12.580 --> 00:12:17.580
You have three main layers
of defense for your health.

00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:21.610
These are the three things
that are constantly at work

00:12:21.610 --> 00:12:26.610
to protect you from invasion
and illness from bacteria,

00:12:27.200 --> 00:12:30.290
from viruses, and from parasites.

00:12:30.290 --> 00:12:34.180
And the first of those
three is a physical barrier

00:12:34.180 --> 00:12:36.120
that we call your skin.

00:12:36.120 --> 00:12:37.500
And that might seem kind of obvious,

00:12:37.500 --> 00:12:42.340
but everything about you is
contained in this compartment

00:12:42.340 --> 00:12:45.350
that is boundaried by your skin.

00:12:45.350 --> 00:12:48.130
And your skin is a very important aspect

00:12:48.130 --> 00:12:49.840
of your immune system.

00:12:49.840 --> 00:12:51.130
If you've ever had a cut,

00:12:51.130 --> 00:12:53.930
you essentially have a
breach of the boundary

00:12:53.930 --> 00:12:55.870
that is your immune system,

00:12:55.870 --> 00:12:58.000
and you would notice a number
of things would happen.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:01.280
You might get some
swelling around that cut.

00:13:01.280 --> 00:13:05.570
You might get a scab, likely
you would get a scab over time.

00:13:05.570 --> 00:13:07.900
If it got dirty, there were
some bacteria that got in there,

00:13:07.900 --> 00:13:10.130
you might see some accumulation
of white blood cells,

00:13:10.130 --> 00:13:10.963
what's called puss.

00:13:10.963 --> 00:13:13.260
I know it's kind of gross,
but that's what that is.

00:13:13.260 --> 00:13:17.090
It might take on a yellow tint
because of the accumulation

00:13:17.090 --> 00:13:18.100
of some dead cells there.

00:13:18.100 --> 00:13:20.760
But basically your skin
is the primary barrier

00:13:20.760 --> 00:13:23.170
through which you keep
things from the outside

00:13:23.170 --> 00:13:26.940
that could harm you from
getting to the inside.

00:13:26.940 --> 00:13:30.640
Now, still in category one,

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:32.810
your body and your external surface,

00:13:32.810 --> 00:13:36.330
you have openings to that surface, right?

00:13:36.330 --> 00:13:40.990
You're not just a round or a body shaped

00:13:40.990 --> 00:13:42.760
completely covered up with skin.

00:13:42.760 --> 00:13:44.330
You have openings, what
are those openings?

00:13:44.330 --> 00:13:47.170
Well, let's start at the
top and work our way down.

00:13:47.170 --> 00:13:51.140
A primary site of potential
infection are your eyes.

00:13:51.140 --> 00:13:53.010
You have your ears,
you have your nostrils,

00:13:53.010 --> 00:13:53.980
you have your mouth.

00:13:53.980 --> 00:13:56.230
Okay, those are going
to be the primary sites

00:13:56.230 --> 00:13:58.930
by which things can get into your system.

00:13:58.930 --> 00:14:00.300
And you need to put
things into your system;

00:14:00.300 --> 00:14:01.320
you need to drink and eat,

00:14:01.320 --> 00:14:02.880
and you need to get
light into your system.

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:04.660
That's why you have those openings,

00:14:04.660 --> 00:14:07.820
but bad things, meaning
things that can harm you,

00:14:07.820 --> 00:14:10.160
can get into those systems.

00:14:10.160 --> 00:14:13.573
And then of course, along
the back of your throat,

00:14:14.820 --> 00:14:18.210
all the way down to your stomach
and your digestive system,

00:14:18.210 --> 00:14:20.300
and through your intestines
and out your rectum,

00:14:20.300 --> 00:14:24.450
you have a tube, that you are
basically a series of tubes.

00:14:24.450 --> 00:14:25.820
I've said that before on this podcast,

00:14:25.820 --> 00:14:28.510
and this is one such tube by
which you extract nutrients

00:14:28.510 --> 00:14:30.170
from the outside environment.

00:14:30.170 --> 00:14:32.500
But all along that tube,

00:14:32.500 --> 00:14:37.180
including your nose and your
mouth, it's lined with mucus.

00:14:37.180 --> 00:14:39.350
And while mucus might seem
kind of gross to some of you,

00:14:39.350 --> 00:14:40.430
the more you learn about mucus,

00:14:40.430 --> 00:14:43.450
the more you realize that
mucus is really, really cool

00:14:43.450 --> 00:14:46.190
because mucus essentially
acts as a filter,

00:14:46.190 --> 00:14:49.460
as a trap for bacteria and viruses.

00:14:49.460 --> 00:14:52.290
And it has certain ways of scrubbing

00:14:52.290 --> 00:14:55.193
or killing those bacteria and viruses.

00:14:56.040 --> 00:14:58.900
Now, the mucus is constantly
being turned over,

00:14:58.900 --> 00:15:00.120
as we'll talk about later,

00:15:00.120 --> 00:15:03.160
the chemistry of that
mucus is really important

00:15:03.160 --> 00:15:06.090
in order to make sure that certain things

00:15:06.090 --> 00:15:07.240
don't make it into your system,

00:15:07.240 --> 00:15:09.440
and other things are allowed
to move through your system

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:11.580
and you can extract nutrients from them.

00:15:11.580 --> 00:15:14.720
So the reason I'm talking
about this first category

00:15:14.720 --> 00:15:17.480
of barrier for immune
system in such detail

00:15:17.480 --> 00:15:21.180
is I'd like you to envision
yourself as a human, of course,

00:15:21.180 --> 00:15:25.550
but as a human that is a clear
entity from everything else.

00:15:25.550 --> 00:15:26.960
And you have to bring in the right things

00:15:26.960 --> 00:15:29.893
and you have to keep out the
wrong things or kill them.

00:15:30.900 --> 00:15:34.530
Now, inevitably, bacteria, viruses,

00:15:34.530 --> 00:15:38.250
and parasitic infections
are going to make their way

00:15:38.250 --> 00:15:41.590
into our body, but whether
or not they are killed off

00:15:41.590 --> 00:15:44.570
or whether or not they
take over and cause us harm

00:15:44.570 --> 00:15:48.100
is going to be determined
by layers two and three.

00:15:48.100 --> 00:15:51.270
So, layers two and three are the so-called

00:15:51.270 --> 00:15:54.660
innate immune system and
the adaptive immune system.

00:15:54.660 --> 00:15:57.180
So the innate immune
system is what I would call

00:15:57.180 --> 00:15:58.370
the second layer of defense.

00:15:58.370 --> 00:15:59.510
It's very fast.

00:15:59.510 --> 00:16:02.910
So whether or not it's
bacteria, virus, or parasite,

00:16:02.910 --> 00:16:06.910
what happens when you have
something enter your body,

00:16:06.910 --> 00:16:09.420
maybe you swallowed it, maybe
got in through your eyes,

00:16:09.420 --> 00:16:12.710
maybe you shook somebody's
hand who is carrying

00:16:12.710 --> 00:16:16.230
a particular kind of illness,
and then you wiped your eyes.

00:16:16.230 --> 00:16:17.860
And I've talked about
on this podcast before,

00:16:17.860 --> 00:16:19.890
very soon after we meet another person,

00:16:19.890 --> 00:16:22.230
usually within 30 seconds,
believe it or not,

00:16:22.230 --> 00:16:24.710
most people wipe that person's chemicals

00:16:24.710 --> 00:16:27.030
somewhere on their face or
on their body's surface.

00:16:27.030 --> 00:16:29.790
This has been demonstrated
over and over again.

00:16:29.790 --> 00:16:30.840
If you want to learn more about that,

00:16:30.840 --> 00:16:32.820
we did an episode all
about chemical signaling,

00:16:32.820 --> 00:16:33.680
where you can learn about it.

00:16:33.680 --> 00:16:36.240
I know it sounds weird and you
might say, "I don't do that,"

00:16:36.240 --> 00:16:41.240
but indeed you do, most of
the time most everybody does.

00:16:41.410 --> 00:16:45.240
Okay, so, this innate immune
system is this rapid response

00:16:45.240 --> 00:16:47.630
when something enters our system

00:16:47.630 --> 00:16:49.960
and our body doesn't recognize it.

00:16:49.960 --> 00:16:52.900
It's not food, it's not clean air,

00:16:52.900 --> 00:16:57.190
it's something that's either
a bacteria, virus or parasite.

00:16:57.190 --> 00:17:01.020
And the innate immune
system involves the release

00:17:01.020 --> 00:17:04.020
of particular cells that
are waiting dormant,

00:17:04.020 --> 00:17:06.680
ready to attack whatever this invader is.

00:17:06.680 --> 00:17:09.520
And some of these cell types
you've heard of before.

00:17:09.520 --> 00:17:12.780
The most typical one are the
so-called white blood cells.

00:17:12.780 --> 00:17:15.890
So, the white blood cells
will actively go to the site

00:17:15.890 --> 00:17:18.750
of invasion and will start to encapsulate

00:17:18.750 --> 00:17:23.040
or try and surround that given invader.

00:17:23.040 --> 00:17:24.750
The other names of these
different cell types

00:17:24.750 --> 00:17:27.160
are things like neutrophils, macrophages,

00:17:27.160 --> 00:17:29.600
natural killer cells are just a few

00:17:29.600 --> 00:17:31.610
of the many types of immune cells.

00:17:31.610 --> 00:17:34.020
So there's kind of like
an ambulance system,

00:17:34.020 --> 00:17:36.210
but rather than go and
try and heal something

00:17:36.210 --> 00:17:38.450
like a paramedic would,
they go there and they try

00:17:38.450 --> 00:17:41.473
and surround and kill
whatever this invader is.

00:17:42.750 --> 00:17:47.750
They work in concert with
two other assistants,

00:17:47.930 --> 00:17:51.210
and those assistants are
called the compliment proteins.

00:17:51.210 --> 00:17:54.240
Compliment proteins exist in the blood,

00:17:54.240 --> 00:17:56.830
and what they do is they travel to sites

00:17:56.830 --> 00:18:00.870
where there's an invasion
and they mark certain things

00:18:00.870 --> 00:18:03.210
for being engulfed and eaten.

00:18:03.210 --> 00:18:06.163
So they sort of put an "eat me" tag on it.

00:18:07.150 --> 00:18:10.260
They basically put a
chemical tag onto invaders

00:18:10.260 --> 00:18:13.390
that then allows those white
blood cells, neutrophils,

00:18:13.390 --> 00:18:15.907
macrophages, natural killer cells to say,

00:18:15.907 --> 00:18:19.610
"Ah, I need to basically kill this thing,

00:18:19.610 --> 00:18:21.530
and then wrap it in a
body bag and send it off.

00:18:21.530 --> 00:18:23.550
Kill that thing, wrap in a
body bag and send it off."

00:18:23.550 --> 00:18:25.510
And I'm using the analogy of the body bag,

00:18:25.510 --> 00:18:29.420
but in the sense it's the right one rather

00:18:29.420 --> 00:18:31.820
because these cells that
come in and kill things,

00:18:31.820 --> 00:18:34.390
the way they do that is actually to engulf

00:18:34.390 --> 00:18:36.760
the invading bacteria, virus or parasite.

00:18:36.760 --> 00:18:38.090
So they actually surround it.

00:18:38.090 --> 00:18:40.930
And when you see puss or you see infection

00:18:42.290 --> 00:18:45.450
in maybe a cut on the skin
or something like that,

00:18:45.450 --> 00:18:49.760
or even in an ingrown hair
that gets some bacteria in it,

00:18:49.760 --> 00:18:52.040
that puss and the white part,

00:18:52.040 --> 00:18:53.270
I know it's kind of gross to talk about,

00:18:53.270 --> 00:18:55.083
but those are the white blood cells,

00:18:56.600 --> 00:18:58.400
oftentimes it's dead cells,

00:18:58.400 --> 00:19:00.450
and that's the dead invader sitting there.

00:19:00.450 --> 00:19:02.720
So it's trying to create
an isolated compartment

00:19:02.720 --> 00:19:04.590
'cause it wants to keep it
in that part of the body.

00:19:04.590 --> 00:19:07.010
Okay, so you've got the
innate immune system,

00:19:07.010 --> 00:19:10.170
the compliment comes
through blood and helps it

00:19:10.170 --> 00:19:12.890
by tagging certain things
with an "eat me" signal.

00:19:12.890 --> 00:19:16.760
And then there are the cells
that are either damaged

00:19:16.760 --> 00:19:19.140
from the injury or from the parasite,

00:19:19.140 --> 00:19:21.840
or are suffering because of the bacteria

00:19:21.840 --> 00:19:26.160
or the virus itself, and
the cells of your body

00:19:26.160 --> 00:19:28.910
will also release an alarm signal,

00:19:28.910 --> 00:19:31.750
which is not an "eat me"
signal, but a "help me" signal.

00:19:31.750 --> 00:19:33.890
And those "help me"
signals come in the form

00:19:33.890 --> 00:19:35.810
of what we call cytokines.

00:19:35.810 --> 00:19:38.480
And the cytokines are
things like interleukin-1,

00:19:38.480 --> 00:19:41.650
interleukin-6, tumor
necrosis factor alpha.

00:19:41.650 --> 00:19:45.310
You may have heard of these
things if you are at all curious

00:19:45.310 --> 00:19:47.500
about or have been learning
about the health space,

00:19:47.500 --> 00:19:49.590
online health space, especially
in the last few years,

00:19:49.590 --> 00:19:51.980
inflammation is all the buzz word now.

00:19:51.980 --> 00:19:53.060
Everyone's talking about inflammation,

00:19:53.060 --> 00:19:54.330
inflammation, inflammation.

00:19:54.330 --> 00:19:56.410
What do we mean when we say inflammation?

00:19:56.410 --> 00:19:58.830
Well, inflammation is a physical response,

00:19:58.830 --> 00:20:01.100
but it's also a chemical response.

00:20:01.100 --> 00:20:05.610
And many times the markers of
inflammation that are measured

00:20:05.610 --> 00:20:10.090
in people or in animal models
where this research is done,

00:20:10.090 --> 00:20:14.120
are things like
interleukin-1, interleukin-6,

00:20:14.120 --> 00:20:15.750
tumor necrosis factor alpha.

00:20:15.750 --> 00:20:17.390
So when those go up in the blood,

00:20:17.390 --> 00:20:19.530
it's a sign that somewhere there's a cell

00:20:19.530 --> 00:20:20.870
that's saying "help me, help me."

00:20:20.870 --> 00:20:23.550
And is secreting these
things which calls in

00:20:23.550 --> 00:20:25.990
those neutrophils, macrophages,
natural killer cells,

00:20:25.990 --> 00:20:27.870
and white blood cells, okay?

00:20:27.870 --> 00:20:30.023
And it might help to remember all this,

00:20:30.023 --> 00:20:34.240
by just telling people
that what interleukin means

00:20:34.240 --> 00:20:36.570
is to communicate, right?

00:20:36.570 --> 00:20:38.560
So the interleukin is
shouting out "help me,"

00:20:38.560 --> 00:20:40.497
the compliment proteins
are coming in and saying,

00:20:40.497 --> 00:20:44.330
"eat this" and tagging the
invader with an "eat me" signal.

00:20:44.330 --> 00:20:46.870
And then the killer cells
and the white blood cells

00:20:46.870 --> 00:20:49.350
are doing the job of trying
to kill off that thing.

00:20:49.350 --> 00:20:51.180
That's the innate immune system.

00:20:51.180 --> 00:20:54.100
So, your skin and your mucus lining

00:20:54.970 --> 00:20:59.970
plus your innate immune system
are a beautiful two-layered

00:21:00.940 --> 00:21:03.560
set of defenses against various kinds

00:21:03.560 --> 00:21:05.590
of invaders and infections.

00:21:05.590 --> 00:21:07.120
And then there's the third type,

00:21:07.120 --> 00:21:09.060
which is the adaptive immune system.

00:21:09.060 --> 00:21:11.350
And you'll notice that
leading up until now,

00:21:11.350 --> 00:21:14.090
I haven't said the word antibody at all,

00:21:14.090 --> 00:21:18.040
and that's because it is
the job not of the skin

00:21:18.040 --> 00:21:22.280
or the mucus or the microbiome
or the innate immune system

00:21:22.280 --> 00:21:25.880
to produce antibodies that can
recognize specific invaders,

00:21:25.880 --> 00:21:29.200
but rather it is the job of
the adaptive immune system

00:21:29.200 --> 00:21:33.770
to create antibodies
against bacteria, viruses,

00:21:33.770 --> 00:21:37.550
and even parasites and
even physical intruders

00:21:37.550 --> 00:21:38.910
to your system.

00:21:38.910 --> 00:21:43.360
So, the adaptive immune system
has this incredible ability

00:21:43.360 --> 00:21:46.000
to show up at the site of invasion

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:47.560
or infection or inflammation.

00:21:47.560 --> 00:21:50.450
It's called there by various cues,

00:21:50.450 --> 00:21:53.410
including the cytokines that
we talked about earlier.

00:21:53.410 --> 00:21:58.410
And what it does is it
actually attaches to

00:21:58.890 --> 00:22:02.720
and creates a sort of
an imprint of the shape

00:22:02.720 --> 00:22:05.440
of whatever invader happens to be there.

00:22:05.440 --> 00:22:09.620
So if that particular
invading bacteria or virus

00:22:09.620 --> 00:22:12.750
has a contour that's kind
of rippled or kind of spiky

00:22:12.750 --> 00:22:15.160
or whatever shape it happens to have,

00:22:15.160 --> 00:22:17.390
it creates an imprint of that.

00:22:17.390 --> 00:22:21.820
And then, using that imprint in concert

00:22:21.820 --> 00:22:25.450
with some other cells, creates
antibodies that are specific

00:22:25.450 --> 00:22:28.260
to recognize that invader should the body

00:22:28.260 --> 00:22:31.210
ever have that invader inside of it again.

00:22:31.210 --> 00:22:33.810
Now, that's why it's called
the adaptive immune system.

00:22:33.810 --> 00:22:38.810
And in many ways it creates
a memory of a prior infection

00:22:38.900 --> 00:22:42.590
so that these antibodies
can be made anytime

00:22:42.590 --> 00:22:44.683
that same invader comes
back again, all right?

00:22:44.683 --> 00:22:47.900
And so, this is the basis
of what we call immunity.

00:22:47.900 --> 00:22:51.610
This is the basis of what
we call an enhanced ability

00:22:51.610 --> 00:22:54.100
to combat certain types of infections.

00:22:54.100 --> 00:22:56.680
And it's really a wonderful, and I mean,

00:22:56.680 --> 00:23:00.840
I can't even state how
incredible this really is,

00:23:00.840 --> 00:23:03.690
that all of our bodies
have this capacity, right?

00:23:03.690 --> 00:23:06.173
We have something called leukocytes.

00:23:07.010 --> 00:23:09.770
These are essentially white blood cells.

00:23:09.770 --> 00:23:11.640
We have red blood cells
and white blood cells,

00:23:11.640 --> 00:23:15.370
and they both are derived from
the same type of origin cell.

00:23:15.370 --> 00:23:16.560
It's a stem cell.

00:23:16.560 --> 00:23:18.820
When you hear stem cell,
a stem cell just means

00:23:18.820 --> 00:23:23.330
a cell that can become many
different types of other cells.

00:23:23.330 --> 00:23:25.860
We sometimes hear about stem
cells in terms of people

00:23:25.860 --> 00:23:27.870
that are getting injections of stem cells

00:23:27.870 --> 00:23:29.930
or the potential therapeutic effects

00:23:30.790 --> 00:23:31.970
or potential of stem cells.

00:23:31.970 --> 00:23:35.250
But we all harbor certain
stem cells within us as well,

00:23:35.250 --> 00:23:37.040
that can become lots of
different cell types.

00:23:37.040 --> 00:23:39.130
And there's one particular
type of stem cell,

00:23:39.130 --> 00:23:41.090
which is the hematopoietic stem cell,

00:23:41.090 --> 00:23:42.990
which can give rise to red blood cells

00:23:42.990 --> 00:23:44.420
and white blood cells.

00:23:44.420 --> 00:23:47.000
And in general, these
reside in the marrow,

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:49.210
at least in adults.

00:23:49.210 --> 00:23:50.400
So, in our bone marrow,

00:23:50.400 --> 00:23:53.210
we have this ability to make certain cells

00:23:53.210 --> 00:23:57.440
that can go out when they
are called out chemically,

00:23:57.440 --> 00:23:59.070
they get called out to sites of infection

00:23:59.070 --> 00:24:00.750
and create antibodies,

00:24:00.750 --> 00:24:03.700
and then maintain those
antibodies in our system,

00:24:03.700 --> 00:24:06.980
or have a memory of that
particular infection

00:24:06.980 --> 00:24:09.090
so that if the infection comes back again,

00:24:09.090 --> 00:24:10.660
we can kill it off immediately.

00:24:10.660 --> 00:24:13.720
And it doesn't have to pass
through these multiple stages

00:24:13.720 --> 00:24:15.130
of first, the innate response,

00:24:15.130 --> 00:24:17.630
then the adaptive
response, taking some time.

00:24:17.630 --> 00:24:18.770
Now, there are a lot more details

00:24:18.770 --> 00:24:20.410
to the adaptive immune system,

00:24:20.410 --> 00:24:23.640
but I just want to emphasize a few points

00:24:23.640 --> 00:24:25.430
that might be relevant.

00:24:25.430 --> 00:24:29.700
First of all, the name of the antibodies

00:24:29.700 --> 00:24:32.100
that are created
sometimes come in the form

00:24:32.100 --> 00:24:36.820
of IgM and IgG, things of that sort.

00:24:36.820 --> 00:24:39.560
This isn't a full deep
dive immunology class,

00:24:39.560 --> 00:24:43.470
but Ig stands for immunoglobulin, okay?

00:24:43.470 --> 00:24:45.330
So the immunoglobulins are a part of

00:24:45.330 --> 00:24:48.773
the adaptive immune response
in creating antibodies.

00:24:49.610 --> 00:24:54.610
If you hear IgM, the IgM is the first

00:24:54.730 --> 00:24:57.270
of the adaptive immune responses,

00:24:57.270 --> 00:24:58.790
and it tends to come on earlier.

00:24:58.790 --> 00:25:02.050
So if somebody is immunopositive for IgM

00:25:02.050 --> 00:25:05.420
for a particular type of
viral or bacterial invader,

00:25:05.420 --> 00:25:08.083
that means that it was a
fairly recent infection.

00:25:08.970 --> 00:25:11.200
Later, one creates...

00:25:11.200 --> 00:25:14.100
The adaptive immune system,
I should say, creates an IgG,

00:25:14.100 --> 00:25:17.020
which is the more stable
form of the specific antibody

00:25:17.020 --> 00:25:19.870
that's going to recognize a given invader.

00:25:19.870 --> 00:25:21.930
So IgG tends to come
up a little bit later.

00:25:21.930 --> 00:25:24.140
So, just to recap,

00:25:24.140 --> 00:25:26.900
something gets into your
system through your eyes,

00:25:26.900 --> 00:25:31.773
through some hole in your skin,
a cut, through your mouth,

00:25:33.160 --> 00:25:35.670
sexually transmitted
diseases come in through

00:25:35.670 --> 00:25:39.210
the mucus membranes that
are on the genitalia

00:25:39.210 --> 00:25:40.563
or in the genitalia,

00:25:41.400 --> 00:25:44.790
sexually transmitted
disease, airborne disease,

00:25:44.790 --> 00:25:47.930
gets into the mucus, somehow
gets into the bloodstream.

00:25:47.930 --> 00:25:50.350
Then there's the innate response,

00:25:50.350 --> 00:25:53.010
which is a more general
response of trying to contain

00:25:53.010 --> 00:25:55.260
and combat the infection or invader.

00:25:55.260 --> 00:25:57.040
And then the adaptive response is the one

00:25:57.040 --> 00:25:58.280
that generates the antibodies.

00:25:58.280 --> 00:26:02.550
First, the IgM response, the
immunoglobulin-M response,

00:26:02.550 --> 00:26:07.060
and then the immunoglobulin-G
response, IgG response.

00:26:07.060 --> 00:26:11.670
So, how do we keep these three barriers

00:26:11.670 --> 00:26:14.950
or these three defense
systems to infection tuned up?

00:26:14.950 --> 00:26:17.670
Well, leaving aside the list of things

00:26:17.670 --> 00:26:19.670
that I mentioned before that generally

00:26:19.670 --> 00:26:20.790
enhances their function,

00:26:20.790 --> 00:26:22.910
things like sleep and
sunlight and good nutrition,

00:26:22.910 --> 00:26:26.600
et cetera, the sort of generic
things for good health,

00:26:26.600 --> 00:26:29.140
one of the key ways we
can do that is to keep

00:26:29.140 --> 00:26:32.070
that mucus lining in really good shape.

00:26:32.070 --> 00:26:32.903
And what does that mean?

00:26:32.903 --> 00:26:36.410
Well, the mucus lining needs
to turn over quite often

00:26:36.410 --> 00:26:39.970
and it needs to be the
correct chemistry to be a trap

00:26:39.970 --> 00:26:44.810
for the bad stuff and
for it to be permeable

00:26:44.810 --> 00:26:47.270
to the good stuff, to the
nutrients that we need.

00:26:47.270 --> 00:26:49.580
And it is now very clear from hundreds,

00:26:49.580 --> 00:26:52.020
if not thousands of studies
that the best way to do that

00:26:52.020 --> 00:26:55.380
is to maintain a healthy
so-called microbiome.

00:26:55.380 --> 00:26:58.740
The microbiome being these
little bacterial organisms

00:26:58.740 --> 00:27:03.640
that are good for us that live
all along our mucus pathways

00:27:03.640 --> 00:27:05.060
and even in our eyes.

00:27:05.060 --> 00:27:07.460
Now, just to be really clear,

00:27:07.460 --> 00:27:09.600
it's not just about the gut microbiome;

00:27:09.600 --> 00:27:11.930
we actually have a microbiome in our eyes,

00:27:11.930 --> 00:27:13.560
we have one that's specific to our mouth,

00:27:13.560 --> 00:27:16.360
we have a nasal specific microbiome,

00:27:16.360 --> 00:27:20.010
there's one all along the gut
and the species of microbiota

00:27:20.010 --> 00:27:22.270
that live all along the digestive tract

00:27:22.270 --> 00:27:25.500
differ from the mouth, to
the throat, to the stomach,

00:27:25.500 --> 00:27:27.180
intestines, into the rectum.

00:27:27.180 --> 00:27:29.760
It's well-established that
there are healthy microbiota

00:27:29.760 --> 00:27:31.280
that live all along that length,

00:27:31.280 --> 00:27:33.780
and that they differ along that length.

00:27:33.780 --> 00:27:36.800
There's also a urethral microbiota,

00:27:36.800 --> 00:27:39.500
and there's a vaginal
microbiota that promotes health

00:27:39.500 --> 00:27:41.210
of that environment as well.

00:27:41.210 --> 00:27:45.570
So how is it that one can
maintain the healthy microbiota

00:27:45.570 --> 00:27:48.980
and not favor growth of harmful bacteria,

00:27:48.980 --> 00:27:52.870
or allow that mucus lining
to become too permeable

00:27:52.870 --> 00:27:55.780
to the bad stuff that can
come in from the environment?

00:27:55.780 --> 00:27:58.000
Well, as far as we know,

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:00.700
there are three main ways to do that.

00:28:00.700 --> 00:28:04.943
The first two are purely
structural and mechanical.

00:28:05.920 --> 00:28:07.880
It's very clear now from work,

00:28:07.880 --> 00:28:11.250
some of which was done at
Stanford, but elsewhere as well,

00:28:11.250 --> 00:28:15.710
that the nasal microbiome
is particularly good

00:28:15.710 --> 00:28:18.870
at scrubbing bacteria,

00:28:18.870 --> 00:28:21.210
at preventing certain types of infections.

00:28:21.210 --> 00:28:24.960
So, this is a reminder
that whenever possible,

00:28:24.960 --> 00:28:28.730
unless eating or speaking, you
want to be nasal breathing,

00:28:28.730 --> 00:28:30.160
not breathing through your mouth.

00:28:30.160 --> 00:28:34.500
Your nose is a much
better filter for viruses

00:28:34.500 --> 00:28:36.520
and bacteria than is your mouth.

00:28:36.520 --> 00:28:38.980
The mouth contains certain
structural features,

00:28:38.980 --> 00:28:42.210
even organs and cell
types that can protect

00:28:42.210 --> 00:28:43.860
against incoming infection,

00:28:43.860 --> 00:28:46.770
but you don't want to be a mouth breather

00:28:46.770 --> 00:28:48.100
for a variety of reasons.

00:28:48.100 --> 00:28:49.407
And there's a terrific book called

00:28:49.407 --> 00:28:51.620
"Jaws: A Hidden Epidemic,"

00:28:51.620 --> 00:28:52.780
which was written by my colleagues,

00:28:52.780 --> 00:28:54.970
Sandra Kahn and Paul Ehrlich at Stanford,

00:28:54.970 --> 00:28:56.530
and Stanford Medicine with a foreword

00:28:56.530 --> 00:28:58.760
by Jared Diamond and Robert Sapolsky.

00:28:58.760 --> 00:29:00.480
So it's really a lot of
heavy hitters on that book

00:29:00.480 --> 00:29:04.090
that talks about the increase in infection

00:29:04.090 --> 00:29:07.620
that one gets when
breathing through the mouth,

00:29:07.620 --> 00:29:08.690
as opposed to the nose.

00:29:08.690 --> 00:29:10.510
Now, of course, during hard exercise,

00:29:10.510 --> 00:29:11.570
one breathes through the mouth,

00:29:11.570 --> 00:29:13.290
that's not necessarily bad.

00:29:13.290 --> 00:29:14.690
When one is eating or speaking,

00:29:14.690 --> 00:29:16.440
that's not necessarily bad at all.

00:29:16.440 --> 00:29:18.000
I guess it depends on what you're saying.

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:18.900
That was a joke.

00:29:18.900 --> 00:29:21.250
But in general, when possible you want

00:29:21.250 --> 00:29:22.690
to be breathing through your nose.

00:29:22.690 --> 00:29:24.700
Many people have trouble
breathing through their nose

00:29:24.700 --> 00:29:26.500
because of so-called deviated septums

00:29:26.500 --> 00:29:28.830
or chronically collapsed sinuses.

00:29:28.830 --> 00:29:31.230
The best way to dilate
those sinuses is actually

00:29:31.230 --> 00:29:32.240
to breathe through your nose.

00:29:32.240 --> 00:29:33.480
So it can take a little bit of time,

00:29:33.480 --> 00:29:36.860
but there is some
plasticity to the sinuses.

00:29:36.860 --> 00:29:39.640
And so, be a nose breather,
not a mouth breather,

00:29:39.640 --> 00:29:42.590
you will combat more of the infections

00:29:42.590 --> 00:29:44.140
that you are constantly confronted with.

00:29:44.140 --> 00:29:46.280
I should mention that
we are always bombarded

00:29:46.280 --> 00:29:48.080
with different types of bacteria, viruses,

00:29:48.080 --> 00:29:49.590
and parasites in our environment.

00:29:49.590 --> 00:29:51.220
And the goal of course,

00:29:51.220 --> 00:29:53.410
is to reinforce your immune system,

00:29:53.410 --> 00:29:56.503
so you can keep these things
at bay and not get sick.

00:29:58.110 --> 00:29:59.580
There's actually a
paper that was published

00:29:59.580 --> 00:30:01.100
in Cell Reports, "Cell Press Journal,"

00:30:01.100 --> 00:30:04.230
excellent journal that showed
that the nasal microbiome,

00:30:04.230 --> 00:30:08.070
it has particular species of microbiota

00:30:08.070 --> 00:30:10.403
that are good at fighting off infection.

00:30:11.460 --> 00:30:14.430
There has not been a direct
link between particular patterns

00:30:14.430 --> 00:30:17.230
of nasal breathing and
the nasal microbiome yet,

00:30:17.230 --> 00:30:19.130
but oxygenation of that environment

00:30:19.130 --> 00:30:20.520
by breathing through your nose,

00:30:20.520 --> 00:30:23.020
turns out to be quite important overall

00:30:23.020 --> 00:30:24.950
for enhancing it as a filter.

00:30:24.950 --> 00:30:26.940
So don't just think of
your nose as something

00:30:26.940 --> 00:30:28.820
to smell foods and to bring in air.

00:30:28.820 --> 00:30:33.730
It's also an active filter for
things that could invade you.

00:30:33.730 --> 00:30:37.920
The other way to try
and keep out bad things

00:30:37.920 --> 00:30:40.470
and to avoid getting sick is
the advice that your mother,

00:30:40.470 --> 00:30:42.280
and certainly my mother gave me,

00:30:42.280 --> 00:30:47.280
which is to not touch your eyes
after touching other people

00:30:48.060 --> 00:30:49.470
or touching other surfaces.

00:30:49.470 --> 00:30:51.530
And as I mentioned earlier,

00:30:51.530 --> 00:30:53.760
we tend to do this subconsciously.

00:30:53.760 --> 00:30:56.170
But the reason to avoid
doing that is the eyes

00:30:56.170 --> 00:31:00.380
are a primary entry point for
a lot of bacteria and viruses.

00:31:00.380 --> 00:31:02.440
You're constantly lubricating
the surface of your eyes

00:31:02.440 --> 00:31:04.020
with the so-called lacrimal glands,

00:31:04.020 --> 00:31:06.720
and tears and things of that sort.

00:31:06.720 --> 00:31:08.260
If you've ever noticed when
you wake up in the morning,

00:31:08.260 --> 00:31:10.197
you have some sleep in your eyes,

00:31:10.197 --> 00:31:11.280
you know the kind of crusty stuff

00:31:11.280 --> 00:31:14.470
in the corners of your
eyes or on your eyelashes,

00:31:14.470 --> 00:31:19.170
that sleep, that crust
are actually dead bacteria

00:31:19.170 --> 00:31:22.740
that you've successfully
battled during the night.

00:31:22.740 --> 00:31:23.573
Okay, that's what that is.

00:31:23.573 --> 00:31:26.660
It's not the accumulation
of some healthy tissue.

00:31:26.660 --> 00:31:30.120
It's the accumulation of that
your healthy mucus membranes

00:31:30.120 --> 00:31:33.390
and tears and other things
that are specifically

00:31:33.390 --> 00:31:35.400
combating those bacteria.

00:31:35.400 --> 00:31:37.090
So, I know that sounds a little bit gross,

00:31:37.090 --> 00:31:37.950
but that's what that is.

00:31:37.950 --> 00:31:41.350
So you're wiping away the
casualties of a battle

00:31:41.350 --> 00:31:43.080
that you fought at night.

00:31:43.080 --> 00:31:45.860
So during the daytime, you
don't want to introduce viruses

00:31:45.860 --> 00:31:48.130
and things to your eyes
as much as possible.

00:31:48.130 --> 00:31:49.700
It is a primary site of entry.

00:31:49.700 --> 00:31:52.920
This is why people wear
goggles in surgical units

00:31:52.920 --> 00:31:54.470
and things of that sort,

00:31:54.470 --> 00:31:57.870
to try and avoid getting
things into their eyes.

00:31:57.870 --> 00:31:59.050
Very, very important.

00:31:59.050 --> 00:32:03.750
And then the third way to
keep a healthy line of defense

00:32:03.750 --> 00:32:08.750
for your entire mucus tract is to enhance

00:32:08.750 --> 00:32:12.200
the proliferation of good gut microbiota.

00:32:12.200 --> 00:32:16.040
The best way to enhance the
quality of your gut microbiome

00:32:16.040 --> 00:32:20.050
and the mucus lining that
serves as this protective layer

00:32:20.050 --> 00:32:24.560
all along your body is to ingest
two to four servings a day

00:32:24.560 --> 00:32:27.210
of fermented foods, low
sugar fermented foods.

00:32:27.210 --> 00:32:28.880
I've talked about this
before a bunch of times

00:32:28.880 --> 00:32:31.180
on the podcast, but these
are data from my colleague,

00:32:31.180 --> 00:32:33.640
Justin Sonnenburg's lab at Stanford Med.

00:32:33.640 --> 00:32:35.160
And there, I just wiped my eyes.

00:32:35.160 --> 00:32:36.093
Yep, you got me.

00:32:37.790 --> 00:32:40.520
But a paper published
in the journal "Cell,"

00:32:40.520 --> 00:32:43.820
which is a absolutely spectacular journal,

00:32:43.820 --> 00:32:45.870
really points to the fact that when

00:32:45.870 --> 00:32:50.210
people eat fermented foods,
two to four servings per day,

00:32:50.210 --> 00:32:53.540
it helps reduce the activity
of certain cytokines.

00:32:53.540 --> 00:32:54.940
Now, you know what those are, right?

00:32:54.940 --> 00:32:57.610
Cells make cytokines to call
out, "help me, help me."

00:32:57.610 --> 00:33:01.190
To reduce the amount of cytokines,

00:33:01.190 --> 00:33:02.450
the so-called inflammatom.

00:33:02.450 --> 00:33:04.490
Now that doesn't render
those cells more vulnerable.

00:33:04.490 --> 00:33:08.190
The reason they saw a
reduction in IL-6 and IL-1,

00:33:08.190 --> 00:33:09.430
and some of these other cytokines

00:33:09.430 --> 00:33:12.370
is because when people have
a healthy gut microbiome,

00:33:12.370 --> 00:33:15.110
there are fewer cells in
the body being infected

00:33:15.110 --> 00:33:18.090
from outside infections and
therefore less of a reason

00:33:18.090 --> 00:33:19.490
for cells to be crying out, "help,"

00:33:19.490 --> 00:33:22.630
because they are thriving, not suffering.

00:33:22.630 --> 00:33:26.280
So, don't wipe your eyes,
keep your hands clean,

00:33:26.280 --> 00:33:27.240
everyone tells you that, right?

00:33:27.240 --> 00:33:29.160
But keep your hands clean,
don't wipe your eyes,

00:33:29.160 --> 00:33:31.260
be a nasal breather, not a mouth breather,

00:33:31.260 --> 00:33:33.900
unless you're speaking,
exercising or eating,

00:33:33.900 --> 00:33:36.250
and keep a healthy gut microbiome

00:33:36.250 --> 00:33:40.190
by eating two to four servings
a day of quality, low sugar,

00:33:40.190 --> 00:33:42.000
fermented foods, things like sauerkraut,

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:44.930
things like natto if you can access that.

00:33:44.930 --> 00:33:46.960
I've tried it before, it's interesting.

00:33:46.960 --> 00:33:50.620
It's sort of an acquired
taste, kimchi, pickles,

00:33:50.620 --> 00:33:53.360
again, low sugar sources
are going to be the sources

00:33:53.360 --> 00:33:55.910
that are going to be
most effective for this.

00:33:55.910 --> 00:33:59.570
So now you're armed with three
ways to enhance the function

00:33:59.570 --> 00:34:03.280
of your immune system and
combat infection that is,

00:34:03.280 --> 00:34:05.050
I like to think separate from the typical

00:34:05.050 --> 00:34:08.610
type of information that you
get such as get good sleep,

00:34:08.610 --> 00:34:10.560
good nutrition, good social
connection, et cetera.

00:34:10.560 --> 00:34:11.860
All of that stuff still holds true,

00:34:11.860 --> 00:34:15.360
but these three other points
I think can really make

00:34:15.360 --> 00:34:17.920
a substantial difference
in terms of bolstering

00:34:17.920 --> 00:34:20.750
the immune system, your immune system.

00:34:20.750 --> 00:34:23.010
I do want to mention,
because these names are going

00:34:23.010 --> 00:34:25.790
to come up several times
during this episode,

00:34:25.790 --> 00:34:30.366
that while interleukins like IL-6 and IL-1

00:34:30.366 --> 00:34:33.460
encourage inflammation, they
are these "help me" signals

00:34:33.460 --> 00:34:36.860
that call in cells to gobble up invaders.

00:34:36.860 --> 00:34:39.480
There are some interleukins
that are anti-inflammatory.

00:34:39.480 --> 00:34:41.550
And the one that I'd like
to highlight in particular,

00:34:41.550 --> 00:34:43.570
because it will come up
again in a little bit

00:34:43.570 --> 00:34:45.250
is interleukin-10.

00:34:45.250 --> 00:34:48.970
So not all of the IL, insert number,

00:34:48.970 --> 00:34:51.500
not all of the interleukins
are inflammatory,

00:34:51.500 --> 00:34:53.900
some are anti-inflammatory.

00:34:53.900 --> 00:34:55.330
So that's an important
point to keep in mind

00:34:55.330 --> 00:34:56.430
as we go forward.

00:34:56.430 --> 00:34:57.720
Next, I'd like to talk about

00:34:57.720 --> 00:34:59.750
what's called sickness behavior.

00:34:59.750 --> 00:35:02.620
And indeed there is a category of behavior

00:35:02.620 --> 00:35:06.860
that we call sickness behavior
that is very informative

00:35:06.860 --> 00:35:10.950
as to the things that we can
do to avoid getting sick.

00:35:10.950 --> 00:35:12.650
Now, this notion of sickness behavior

00:35:12.650 --> 00:35:15.010
goes back several decades or more.

00:35:15.010 --> 00:35:18.300
And it's a very interesting way of looking

00:35:18.300 --> 00:35:20.520
at the function of the immune system,

00:35:20.520 --> 00:35:24.430
because what it does is it
bridges us from this thing

00:35:24.430 --> 00:35:27.200
that we're calling the immune
system where it's T-cells,

00:35:27.200 --> 00:35:30.280
and B-cells, and cytokines and leukocytes,

00:35:30.280 --> 00:35:31.760
and it starts taking us into the realm

00:35:31.760 --> 00:35:32.593
of the nervous system,

00:35:32.593 --> 00:35:35.670
because of course the nervous
system controls behavior.

00:35:35.670 --> 00:35:40.080
So sickness behavior
is a suite of responses

00:35:40.080 --> 00:35:44.220
that we tend to all undergo
when we are feeling sick.

00:35:44.220 --> 00:35:47.690
So this is going to vary
from person to person,

00:35:47.690 --> 00:35:49.410
but there's some general
categories of things

00:35:49.410 --> 00:35:52.220
that we all do and that
happen to all of us

00:35:52.220 --> 00:35:54.210
after we are wounded or sick

00:35:54.210 --> 00:35:56.050
or dealing with an infection of any kind.

00:35:56.050 --> 00:35:59.540
And by examining sickness
behavior in some detail,

00:35:59.540 --> 00:36:02.470
it can be really informative as to routes

00:36:02.470 --> 00:36:04.030
that we can take to health.

00:36:04.030 --> 00:36:07.010
So the main thing about sickness behavior

00:36:07.010 --> 00:36:09.570
is that it tends to involve a slowing

00:36:09.570 --> 00:36:11.580
of our usual levels of activity.

00:36:11.580 --> 00:36:13.640
People start to feel lethargic,

00:36:13.640 --> 00:36:16.680
or they feel like the
activities that previously

00:36:16.680 --> 00:36:18.610
they could do with relative ease

00:36:18.610 --> 00:36:22.450
are very difficult for them
or somewhat overwhelming.

00:36:22.450 --> 00:36:25.160
The other thing you start to
see is that people and animals,

00:36:25.160 --> 00:36:27.400
by the way, stop grooming,

00:36:27.400 --> 00:36:28.930
they stop taking care of themselves.

00:36:28.930 --> 00:36:30.340
Not necessarily stopped showering,

00:36:30.340 --> 00:36:31.680
although oftentimes that's the case,

00:36:31.680 --> 00:36:34.310
but they will stop doing their hair,

00:36:34.310 --> 00:36:35.923
they'll stop putting on makeup,

00:36:36.880 --> 00:36:38.930
depending on whether or
not they did that before,

00:36:38.930 --> 00:36:39.763
they might stop.

00:36:39.763 --> 00:36:43.100
Animals will stop licking
and grooming themselves.

00:36:43.100 --> 00:36:46.800
People will stop taking care
of their cosmetic appearance.

00:36:46.800 --> 00:36:49.340
Now it's not just because they don't care

00:36:49.340 --> 00:36:50.460
how they look when they're sick,

00:36:50.460 --> 00:36:53.320
it's because there's
this overall suppression

00:36:53.320 --> 00:36:55.930
of certain kinds of
activities and an enhancement

00:36:55.930 --> 00:36:57.070
of other kinds of activities.

00:36:57.070 --> 00:36:59.270
And this is really important.

00:36:59.270 --> 00:37:03.010
Sickness behavior is
actually a motivated state.

00:37:03.010 --> 00:37:06.760
It's a state that's designed
to accomplish certain things.

00:37:06.760 --> 00:37:09.610
One of the other features
of sickness behavior

00:37:09.610 --> 00:37:12.160
in addition to being
lethargic, loss of grooming,

00:37:12.160 --> 00:37:15.830
will be a loss of appetite, right?

00:37:15.830 --> 00:37:18.360
Oftentimes people who have
a great appetite normally

00:37:18.360 --> 00:37:20.260
just won't feel hungry at all.

00:37:20.260 --> 00:37:22.620
And there are several theories
as to why this would be.

00:37:22.620 --> 00:37:26.330
One prominent idea in
the literature is that

00:37:26.330 --> 00:37:29.960
it's to discourage vomiting and diarrhea,

00:37:29.960 --> 00:37:33.350
which of course can be
infectious to other people.

00:37:33.350 --> 00:37:35.120
So, that's a theory.

00:37:35.120 --> 00:37:37.540
I don't know that that's
ever been tested directly,

00:37:37.540 --> 00:37:39.240
but that's one idea.

00:37:39.240 --> 00:37:43.410
The other idea is that it's
simply to harbor more resources

00:37:43.410 --> 00:37:44.810
for sake of repair.

00:37:44.810 --> 00:37:48.780
And I want to talk about
that because we are all told

00:37:48.780 --> 00:37:52.490
to get extra sleep when we
aren't feeling well or to rest.

00:37:52.490 --> 00:37:55.720
But just like any good
two or three-year-old

00:37:55.720 --> 00:37:58.300
constantly asks, "why, why?"

00:37:58.300 --> 00:38:02.430
Good scientists, good
people who are interested

00:38:02.430 --> 00:38:05.260
in health information
should always be asking why.

00:38:05.260 --> 00:38:06.270
Why should I get more sleep?

00:38:06.270 --> 00:38:08.420
What happens in sleep that I should

00:38:08.420 --> 00:38:09.550
get more sleep when I'm sick?

00:38:09.550 --> 00:38:11.180
Why shouldn't I just push through this?

00:38:11.180 --> 00:38:13.330
And there are a couple of reasons for this

00:38:13.330 --> 00:38:15.180
that have been established
in the literature.

00:38:15.180 --> 00:38:18.550
The first is that there does
seem to be something useful

00:38:18.550 --> 00:38:21.870
about slowing circulation when we are ill.

00:38:21.870 --> 00:38:24.380
One idea that has some data to support it

00:38:24.380 --> 00:38:28.590
is that when we slow our
circulation, our blood circulation,

00:38:28.590 --> 00:38:30.950
so not running around so
much or running it all,

00:38:30.950 --> 00:38:35.230
but rather lying down, getting
extra rest, maybe sleeping,

00:38:35.230 --> 00:38:37.280
maybe even just remaining still,

00:38:37.280 --> 00:38:39.430
is that the lymphatic system,

00:38:39.430 --> 00:38:42.600
which carries a lot of the
immune-related cells and fluids,

00:38:42.600 --> 00:38:45.580
is able to ramp up its levels of activity.

00:38:45.580 --> 00:38:46.890
So, this is interesting, right?

00:38:46.890 --> 00:38:49.270
So reducing circulation of the blood,

00:38:49.270 --> 00:38:52.870
but increasing circulation
of the lymphatic system.

00:38:52.870 --> 00:38:55.960
You've all probably been familiar
with the lymphatic system

00:38:55.960 --> 00:38:57.670
when you're combating an infection,

00:38:57.670 --> 00:38:59.370
your lymph nodes can get sore.

00:38:59.370 --> 00:39:00.770
You've got lymph nodes behind your ears,

00:39:00.770 --> 00:39:02.950
in your groin, your
armpits, around your throat,

00:39:02.950 --> 00:39:06.590
around near your thyroid,
in your throat, et cetera.

00:39:06.590 --> 00:39:08.940
So, that's the other reason.

00:39:08.940 --> 00:39:10.893
Now, some people, when they get sick,

00:39:13.270 --> 00:39:16.850
psychologically go into
a very vulnerable state

00:39:16.850 --> 00:39:19.220
where they really, really want people,

00:39:19.220 --> 00:39:20.900
other people to take care of them.

00:39:20.900 --> 00:39:22.880
You've probably witnessed this,

00:39:22.880 --> 00:39:25.330
or you feel this way yourself.

00:39:25.330 --> 00:39:27.690
About 50% of people have that response.

00:39:27.690 --> 00:39:29.410
They really want to be taken care of.

00:39:29.410 --> 00:39:32.020
Now, when you think about it
from an adaptive perspective,

00:39:32.020 --> 00:39:33.530
this makes sense, right?

00:39:33.530 --> 00:39:37.530
A member of our species is
ill and they more or less

00:39:37.530 --> 00:39:40.860
will cry out for help
in one form or another

00:39:40.860 --> 00:39:44.240
to the other members of their
species to take care of them.

00:39:44.240 --> 00:39:47.360
And of course this will be
especially apparent in cases

00:39:47.360 --> 00:39:50.160
where people are young enough
or incapacitated enough

00:39:50.160 --> 00:39:52.770
that they can't actually
get resources on their own.

00:39:52.770 --> 00:39:53.750
If you've ever been really sick,

00:39:53.750 --> 00:39:56.540
just getting up and going to
the fridge or to the restroom

00:39:56.540 --> 00:39:59.960
can feel like a monumental task.

00:39:59.960 --> 00:40:04.960
So about 50% of people report
or describe seeking of help

00:40:05.230 --> 00:40:06.700
and support when they are sick.

00:40:06.700 --> 00:40:09.130
But you could also
imagine how this would be

00:40:09.130 --> 00:40:11.850
a very non-adaptive response

00:40:11.850 --> 00:40:15.170
because it increases the
opportunity to spread infection

00:40:15.170 --> 00:40:16.410
to the caretaker.

00:40:16.410 --> 00:40:19.243
So that's an interesting consideration.

00:40:20.140 --> 00:40:24.770
Another 50% of people seem
to have the opposite response

00:40:24.770 --> 00:40:25.603
when they're sick.

00:40:25.603 --> 00:40:28.170
So, somehow, regardless of how they were

00:40:28.170 --> 00:40:29.840
prior to getting ill,

00:40:29.840 --> 00:40:32.220
the sickness behavior that's engaged

00:40:32.220 --> 00:40:34.080
by these neural circuits in the brain,

00:40:34.080 --> 00:40:35.800
they are indeed neural
circuits in the brain,

00:40:35.800 --> 00:40:37.680
create a stay away from me.

00:40:37.680 --> 00:40:38.700
I don't want to be bothered.

00:40:38.700 --> 00:40:39.700
I want to be left alone.

00:40:39.700 --> 00:40:41.280
I don't want to be taken care of, right?

00:40:41.280 --> 00:40:42.823
It's not stubbornness.

00:40:43.921 --> 00:40:45.970
It's literally a lack of interest

00:40:45.970 --> 00:40:48.680
or a disinterest in social
connection when one is sick.

00:40:48.680 --> 00:40:50.200
And you see this in animals too,

00:40:50.200 --> 00:40:52.960
some animals will seek out
other members of their species.

00:40:52.960 --> 00:40:54.730
Others, like my unfortunately now

00:40:54.730 --> 00:40:56.580
passed away bulldog, Costello.

00:40:56.580 --> 00:40:59.220
When he was sick I always knew
because he would go around

00:40:59.220 --> 00:41:00.740
the back of the house and
he would just hide there.

00:41:00.740 --> 00:41:03.640
He would just take himself
away from everybody else.

00:41:03.640 --> 00:41:05.677
He did not want to be taken care of.

00:41:05.677 --> 00:41:07.530
And it was just a natural response to him.

00:41:07.530 --> 00:41:08.880
I don't think he was trying to prevent me

00:41:08.880 --> 00:41:11.190
from getting whatever it was that he had.

00:41:11.190 --> 00:41:14.440
So if ever somebody doesn't
want to be taken care of,

00:41:14.440 --> 00:41:15.690
or if they do want to be taken care of,

00:41:15.690 --> 00:41:17.350
realize that people tend to fall into

00:41:17.350 --> 00:41:19.430
these two bins naturally,

00:41:19.430 --> 00:41:21.930
and animals tend to fall into these bins.

00:41:21.930 --> 00:41:24.940
Regardless of what species
they are, it's about 50/50.

00:41:24.940 --> 00:41:28.510
And again, this sickness
behavior is a motivated state.

00:41:28.510 --> 00:41:31.610
It's designed to slow
circulation of the blood,

00:41:31.610 --> 00:41:33.560
increase circulation of the lymph,

00:41:33.560 --> 00:41:36.360
and the other killer cells in the body,

00:41:36.360 --> 00:41:40.130
reduce the probability of
infecting others by reducing,

00:41:40.130 --> 00:41:42.060
its thought, diarrhea and vomit,

00:41:42.060 --> 00:41:45.260
but also breathing on others,
interacting with others.

00:41:45.260 --> 00:41:48.350
And in some cases it will activate this,

00:41:48.350 --> 00:41:50.080
I don't want to call it a regressed state,

00:41:50.080 --> 00:41:52.685
but many people feel somewhat more...

00:41:52.685 --> 00:41:55.700
If they are adults,
they feel more childlike

00:41:55.700 --> 00:41:56.950
when they are ill and they want

00:41:56.950 --> 00:41:58.390
to be taken care of very badly.

00:41:58.390 --> 00:41:59.330
Some of it might be learned.

00:41:59.330 --> 00:42:01.560
Some of it might be innate.

00:42:01.560 --> 00:42:05.080
We don't know, but the sickness
behavior is very interesting

00:42:05.080 --> 00:42:06.130
for a couple of reasons.

00:42:06.130 --> 00:42:09.170
First of all, it mimics another state

00:42:09.170 --> 00:42:11.800
that has been described in
the neuroscience literature,

00:42:11.800 --> 00:42:13.593
which is major depression.

00:42:14.840 --> 00:42:17.810
And in both sick individuals,

00:42:17.810 --> 00:42:20.200
sick from bacterial or viral infection,

00:42:20.200 --> 00:42:21.770
and in people with major depression,

00:42:21.770 --> 00:42:24.800
it's been shown that
there are robust increases

00:42:24.800 --> 00:42:27.760
in the levels of interleukin-6

00:42:27.760 --> 00:42:29.840
and tumor necrosis factor alpha.

00:42:29.840 --> 00:42:34.530
So there is an idea now circulating
that depression involves

00:42:34.530 --> 00:42:37.630
these inflammatory
cytokines being very active.

00:42:37.630 --> 00:42:39.830
And we know that illness involves

00:42:39.830 --> 00:42:42.230
inflammatory cytokines being very active.

00:42:42.230 --> 00:42:43.063
So if you think about it,

00:42:43.063 --> 00:42:45.970
the similarity between major
depression and being sick

00:42:46.960 --> 00:42:49.990
ought to be able to point us
in a direction of interventions

00:42:49.990 --> 00:42:52.710
that could help us either prevent illness

00:42:52.710 --> 00:42:55.140
or move through illness more quickly.

00:42:55.140 --> 00:42:58.200
But as we head in that direction,

00:42:58.200 --> 00:43:00.060
because indeed that's the case,

00:43:00.060 --> 00:43:02.770
I just want to emphasize
that sickness behavior

00:43:02.770 --> 00:43:06.250
is what provides this bridge
between the immune system

00:43:06.250 --> 00:43:07.770
and the nervous system.

00:43:07.770 --> 00:43:11.440
And what we'll soon see also
is that healthy behavior,

00:43:11.440 --> 00:43:13.700
behavior that allows
us to avoid infection,

00:43:13.700 --> 00:43:16.620
also points to a clear bridge between

00:43:16.620 --> 00:43:18.840
the nervous system and the immune system.

00:43:18.840 --> 00:43:20.630
That it isn't just that we have a brain

00:43:20.630 --> 00:43:23.070
and body and our organs, and
then we have an immune system.

00:43:23.070 --> 00:43:25.960
That's true, but they're
interacting all the time.

00:43:25.960 --> 00:43:28.000
And this is going to lead us to a place

00:43:28.000 --> 00:43:31.870
where it's going to be very
clear and not at all surprising

00:43:31.870 --> 00:43:34.820
how certain patterns of
thinking and certain behaviors

00:43:34.820 --> 00:43:37.870
that we can elect to take can help enhance

00:43:37.870 --> 00:43:40.720
our immune system function and vice versa.

00:43:40.720 --> 00:43:43.210
There are two other features
of sickness behavior

00:43:43.210 --> 00:43:45.250
definitely worth pointing out.

00:43:45.250 --> 00:43:48.710
One is a theory, which is
that the reduced appetite,

00:43:48.710 --> 00:43:53.350
in particular appetite for
protein rich foods when sick,

00:43:53.350 --> 00:43:58.180
is thought to be an attempt,
a subconscious attempt,

00:43:58.180 --> 00:44:01.610
of the organism to
reduce the amount of iron

00:44:01.610 --> 00:44:02.900
that it's taking in.

00:44:02.900 --> 00:44:05.510
Now, typically the amount of iron intake

00:44:06.610 --> 00:44:09.480
that's recommended or
more or less is for men,

00:44:09.480 --> 00:44:11.790
it's about eight milligrams per day.

00:44:11.790 --> 00:44:14.780
For women, it's anywhere from
18 to 27 milligrams per day,

00:44:14.780 --> 00:44:16.260
depending on whether or
not they're pregnant,

00:44:16.260 --> 00:44:20.133
lactating or menstruating, et
cetera, the ranges can vary.

00:44:21.270 --> 00:44:24.300
But, and indeed, it's
true that if iron levels

00:44:24.300 --> 00:44:28.930
in the blood go too high, like
over 45 milligrams per day

00:44:28.930 --> 00:44:30.950
can be very toxic to the system.

00:44:30.950 --> 00:44:34.760
But the theory that's prominent
in the biology literature

00:44:34.760 --> 00:44:37.070
and in the health literature
is that the reduction

00:44:37.070 --> 00:44:38.570
in appetite is actually an attempt

00:44:38.570 --> 00:44:42.550
to reduce iron intake specifically

00:44:42.550 --> 00:44:45.560
because many bacteria and
other forms of infection

00:44:45.560 --> 00:44:49.567
seem to thrive when levels of
iron in the blood are high.

00:44:49.567 --> 00:44:51.890
And I don't want to see
anyone take this too extreme

00:44:51.890 --> 00:44:53.740
and suddenly do an iron deprivation diet

00:44:53.740 --> 00:44:55.990
in order to get well.

00:44:55.990 --> 00:44:58.200
But it's an interesting
theory that I'd be remiss

00:44:58.200 --> 00:45:01.560
if I didn't mention,
because it makes good sense.

00:45:01.560 --> 00:45:04.830
Iron is actually attached to hemoglobin

00:45:04.830 --> 00:45:06.790
and red blood cells in the bloodstream.

00:45:06.790 --> 00:45:10.260
Normally that can help us quite a lot.

00:45:10.260 --> 00:45:12.160
It's also in muscle,
I should mention that.

00:45:12.160 --> 00:45:14.380
Iron can be a sequestered into muscle,

00:45:14.380 --> 00:45:19.130
and iron serves a lot of
important health promoting roles,

00:45:19.130 --> 00:45:24.130
but by reducing appetite and
thereby reducing iron intake,

00:45:24.650 --> 00:45:27.170
it does reduce the
capacity of certain things,

00:45:27.170 --> 00:45:30.420
including infections to
travel in certain compartments

00:45:30.420 --> 00:45:31.610
within the body.

00:45:31.610 --> 00:45:33.360
So, again, that's just theory,

00:45:33.360 --> 00:45:35.630
but I think many of you
are probably familiar

00:45:35.630 --> 00:45:38.533
with not having an
appetite when you're sick.

00:45:39.980 --> 00:45:43.570
The other thing that's
very typical of people

00:45:43.570 --> 00:45:46.210
with major depression is loss of appetite,

00:45:46.210 --> 00:45:47.870
not always but often loss of appetite.

00:45:47.870 --> 00:45:49.760
So, here again, we have loss of appetite

00:45:49.760 --> 00:45:52.590
in sickness behavior, loss of
appetite and major depression,

00:45:52.590 --> 00:45:56.780
and perhaps not surprisingly
one of the major symptoms

00:45:56.780 --> 00:45:59.110
of sickness behavior and major depression

00:45:59.110 --> 00:46:01.920
that map more or less onto one another

00:46:01.920 --> 00:46:04.310
is loss of libido or interest,

00:46:04.310 --> 00:46:05.750
not just in social interactions,

00:46:05.750 --> 00:46:07.340
but in sex and reproduction.

00:46:07.340 --> 00:46:09.820
And so, again, if you think
about sickness behavior

00:46:09.820 --> 00:46:12.950
and depression, they
are very, very similar.

00:46:12.950 --> 00:46:15.780
Okay, so sickness behavior
and major depression

00:46:15.780 --> 00:46:19.343
have certain core features in common.

00:46:20.420 --> 00:46:24.800
We need to therefore ask
ourselves why and how does

00:46:24.800 --> 00:46:28.510
being sick influence the way
that we think and perceive

00:46:28.510 --> 00:46:32.570
our environment and impact our appetite,

00:46:32.570 --> 00:46:34.450
whether or not we want
to be cared for more

00:46:34.450 --> 00:46:35.450
or cared for less?

00:46:35.450 --> 00:46:39.070
Again, people tend to diverge
into two different bins there,

00:46:39.070 --> 00:46:40.380
and believe it or not,

00:46:40.380 --> 00:46:43.800
the pathway for this has been identified.

00:46:43.800 --> 00:46:47.330
When we have an infection
someplace in our body,

00:46:47.330 --> 00:46:48.890
and it could be up in our head,

00:46:48.890 --> 00:46:51.940
it could be a sinus infection,
it could be an ear infection,

00:46:51.940 --> 00:46:55.770
or I should also mention
many of these same mechanisms

00:46:55.770 --> 00:46:57.820
can also be the consequence of a wound

00:46:57.820 --> 00:46:59.453
or an injury to the body.

00:47:01.167 --> 00:47:02.700
A back injury or a slipped disc

00:47:02.700 --> 00:47:04.740
or I guess it's called a herniated disc

00:47:04.740 --> 00:47:07.740
is the way that you hear it described.

00:47:07.740 --> 00:47:10.120
When we have that, we
can be kind of irritable,

00:47:10.120 --> 00:47:11.810
we don't want to do certain things

00:47:11.810 --> 00:47:13.940
and we just want to be left alone.

00:47:13.940 --> 00:47:14.810
Things are harder.

00:47:14.810 --> 00:47:16.190
How? Why?

00:47:16.190 --> 00:47:18.960
Well, there's a known pathway,

00:47:18.960 --> 00:47:21.870
which is the so-called vagus nerve

00:47:21.870 --> 00:47:24.390
that connects the body and the brain,

00:47:24.390 --> 00:47:29.390
signals to particular brain
sites to engage this category

00:47:29.630 --> 00:47:32.563
of motivational state that
we call sickness behavior.

00:47:33.680 --> 00:47:35.820
Many of you have probably
heard of the vagus,

00:47:35.820 --> 00:47:38.440
V-A-G-U-S, vagus.

00:47:38.440 --> 00:47:40.850
The vagus nerve is a very
extensive nerve pathway,

00:47:40.850 --> 00:47:43.940
as the 10th cranial nerve
comes out of the back

00:47:43.940 --> 00:47:47.040
of the brainstem, heads into the body,

00:47:47.040 --> 00:47:50.560
and branches out extensively to innervate

00:47:50.560 --> 00:47:53.210
or connect to many of our organs,

00:47:53.210 --> 00:47:55.440
including our lungs, our
heart, our gut, et cetera.

00:47:55.440 --> 00:47:59.390
And all of those organs are
able also to send neural signals

00:47:59.390 --> 00:48:00.513
back up to the brain.

00:48:01.530 --> 00:48:04.070
We sometimes hear of
the vagus as the route

00:48:04.070 --> 00:48:06.630
to calming ourselves down.

00:48:06.630 --> 00:48:08.960
Unfortunately, that's more or less a myth

00:48:08.960 --> 00:48:11.000
that I don't know how it got propagated.

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:13.100
You have lots of different
pathways in the vagus

00:48:13.100 --> 00:48:16.540
Usually vagal stimulation
actually creates more arousal

00:48:16.540 --> 00:48:19.210
and alertness, although it
does have multiple pathways,

00:48:19.210 --> 00:48:23.550
but there have now been
many studies of the vagus

00:48:23.550 --> 00:48:25.940
in various contexts, including
in sickness behavior.

00:48:25.940 --> 00:48:30.940
And it's very clear that the
vagus nerve is the fast pathway

00:48:31.370 --> 00:48:34.890
by which an infection in the
body is signaled to the brain,

00:48:34.890 --> 00:48:36.240
to a particular location in the brain

00:48:36.240 --> 00:48:37.430
called the hypothalamus,

00:48:37.430 --> 00:48:40.220
which harbors a lot of
different types of neurons.

00:48:40.220 --> 00:48:42.310
Neurons, for instance,
in the preoptic area

00:48:42.310 --> 00:48:45.290
that increase body
temperature and fever, right?

00:48:45.290 --> 00:48:46.600
That's one of the most important things

00:48:46.600 --> 00:48:49.130
is to increase body temperature,

00:48:49.130 --> 00:48:52.930
it's the body's attempt
to kill off this invader

00:48:52.930 --> 00:48:57.040
because many viruses and many bacteria

00:48:57.040 --> 00:48:59.240
don't survive well at elevated heat.

00:48:59.240 --> 00:49:00.560
That's the function of a fever.

00:49:00.560 --> 00:49:02.190
A fever actually has a functional role.

00:49:02.190 --> 00:49:05.010
So, in biology, we like complicated words,

00:49:05.010 --> 00:49:07.820
so we call anything that
increases body temperature

00:49:07.820 --> 00:49:11.060
or creates a fever, a pyrogen.

00:49:11.060 --> 00:49:14.130
Many years ago, in my undergraduate years,

00:49:14.130 --> 00:49:16.340
I was working on pyrogens,

00:49:16.340 --> 00:49:19.220
injecting something
called lipopolysaccharide

00:49:19.220 --> 00:49:22.910
into the belly, which
then gives you a fever.

00:49:22.910 --> 00:49:25.390
The way it does that is LPS causes

00:49:25.390 --> 00:49:28.040
an inflammation response in the gut.

00:49:28.040 --> 00:49:29.650
The gut doesn't know what is happening.

00:49:29.650 --> 00:49:31.560
The stomach cells don't
know what's happening.

00:49:31.560 --> 00:49:35.900
So they just start secreting
the IL-6, the IL-1,

00:49:35.900 --> 00:49:38.760
all those cytokines, the killer
cells migrate into the gut.

00:49:38.760 --> 00:49:40.320
That's why you sometimes
get a stomach ache

00:49:40.320 --> 00:49:41.960
when you don't feel well, you have a flu,

00:49:41.960 --> 00:49:43.023
or something like it.

00:49:44.170 --> 00:49:46.330
A neural signal, electrical
signals get sent up

00:49:46.330 --> 00:49:47.400
to the hypothalamus.

00:49:47.400 --> 00:49:49.470
The hypothalamus says, oh,
I don't know what's going on

00:49:49.470 --> 00:49:51.560
out there, but there's a
signal something's going on.

00:49:51.560 --> 00:49:53.170
Let's just heat up the body.

00:49:53.170 --> 00:49:56.040
Let's just start cooking
whatever it is out there.

00:49:56.040 --> 00:49:57.840
And of course you don't
want fever to go too high

00:49:57.840 --> 00:49:59.560
because you can kill brain cells.

00:49:59.560 --> 00:50:04.560
But within a particular range
the fever is a functional

00:50:05.090 --> 00:50:06.810
and adaptive response, okay?

00:50:06.810 --> 00:50:09.750
So if you're taking drugs
to try and lower the fever

00:50:09.750 --> 00:50:11.180
that might make you feel more comfortable,

00:50:11.180 --> 00:50:14.610
but actually that's limiting
the response that your body

00:50:14.610 --> 00:50:17.920
is creating in order to try
and kill off that invader.

00:50:17.920 --> 00:50:20.960
And again, you don't want
fever to go too high.

00:50:20.960 --> 00:50:23.480
This is going to vary depending on age.

00:50:23.480 --> 00:50:26.060
You can look up online what the tolerable

00:50:26.060 --> 00:50:27.260
ranges are for fever.

00:50:27.260 --> 00:50:29.820
But when you're trying
to lower body temperature

00:50:29.820 --> 00:50:31.400
when you have a fever,

00:50:31.400 --> 00:50:34.850
unless you're heading into
dangerous levels of heating up,

00:50:34.850 --> 00:50:36.920
that's actually the wrong
way to take your system

00:50:36.920 --> 00:50:40.220
if you do indeed want to
kill off that invader.

00:50:40.220 --> 00:50:42.330
Okay, so the vagus nerve
is the quick response.

00:50:42.330 --> 00:50:46.730
It also sends input to areas of the brain

00:50:46.730 --> 00:50:49.240
that change your perception
of the outside world.

00:50:49.240 --> 00:50:51.900
One of the most obvious of these,

00:50:51.900 --> 00:50:56.090
obvious once I tell it to
you, is photophobia, right?

00:50:56.090 --> 00:50:57.490
I love bright sunshine.

00:50:57.490 --> 00:51:00.140
I love bright lights
when I want to be alert.

00:51:00.140 --> 00:51:02.980
We all have different
levels of light sensitivity,

00:51:02.980 --> 00:51:05.810
but most people when they are sick,

00:51:05.810 --> 00:51:08.450
when there's an inflammation
response in the body,

00:51:08.450 --> 00:51:10.670
they feel like bright
lights are kind of aversive.

00:51:10.670 --> 00:51:14.100
They get a well-described
kind of classical photophobia,

00:51:14.100 --> 00:51:17.840
and that's mediated by a
pathway that goes from your eye

00:51:17.840 --> 00:51:20.910
to an area of your thalamus,

00:51:20.910 --> 00:51:24.080
called the anterior
nucleus of the thalamus.

00:51:24.080 --> 00:51:26.030
This is work that was
done by Clifford Saper

00:51:26.030 --> 00:51:27.920
at Harvard Medical School.

00:51:27.920 --> 00:51:30.020
It's really beautiful work.

00:51:30.020 --> 00:51:34.620
And then from there up to the
outer lining of the brain,

00:51:34.620 --> 00:51:36.720
which is the meninges just sort of

00:51:36.720 --> 00:51:38.890
on the outside of the brain
where the brain starts

00:51:38.890 --> 00:51:41.420
to interface with some of
the other connective tissues.

00:51:41.420 --> 00:51:43.080
We'll talk more about these later.

00:51:43.080 --> 00:51:46.580
It can actually create a
photophobia and a headache

00:51:46.580 --> 00:51:47.530
when one is ill.

00:51:47.530 --> 00:51:49.729
So, here's the pathway:

00:51:49.729 --> 00:51:51.950
Some invader gets into your system

00:51:51.950 --> 00:51:53.970
'cause you wiped your eyes or
it got in through your mouth.

00:51:53.970 --> 00:51:55.190
You didn't listen to your mother

00:51:55.190 --> 00:51:57.150
and got in through your eyes.

00:51:57.150 --> 00:51:58.233
You're feeling sick.

00:51:59.140 --> 00:52:00.020
Something's going on there.

00:52:00.020 --> 00:52:01.420
You have a stomach ache because of all

00:52:01.420 --> 00:52:03.230
the inflammation there,

00:52:03.230 --> 00:52:05.580
the signal goes up from your vagus nerve.

00:52:05.580 --> 00:52:07.350
You're heating up with a fever.

00:52:07.350 --> 00:52:10.880
You've got photophobia
because you've activated

00:52:10.880 --> 00:52:15.280
this pathway by which what would
normally be tolerable light

00:52:15.280 --> 00:52:19.140
is triggering this thalamic
nucleus, the anterior thalamus,

00:52:19.140 --> 00:52:20.840
that's projecting up to the meninges.

00:52:20.840 --> 00:52:23.170
You got a headache in
response to looking at light.

00:52:23.170 --> 00:52:25.360
It's basically triggering
an overall pathway

00:52:25.360 --> 00:52:28.440
to get you to go into a
quiet, dark place and rest.

00:52:28.440 --> 00:52:31.450
And the last element I'd like
to talk about is the rest.

00:52:31.450 --> 00:52:34.230
There's something that gets
triggered from the body

00:52:34.230 --> 00:52:35.980
to the brain, to the hypothalamus,

00:52:35.980 --> 00:52:38.510
and we think we know which
hypothalamic area it is.

00:52:38.510 --> 00:52:40.780
It's the supraoptic nucleus, we think.

00:52:40.780 --> 00:52:42.300
Supraoptic 'cause it's right above

00:52:42.300 --> 00:52:44.020
your so-called optic chiasm,

00:52:44.020 --> 00:52:45.140
If you want to look up where that is,

00:52:45.140 --> 00:52:46.750
it's right above the roof of your mouth.

00:52:46.750 --> 00:52:51.750
And there are nuclei there that
promote the desire to sleep

00:52:52.090 --> 00:52:55.070
even during the daytime,
what would normally be

00:52:55.070 --> 00:52:57.840
the active phase of your circadian cycle.

00:52:57.840 --> 00:53:00.100
Now, that is really interesting

00:53:00.100 --> 00:53:02.750
because what's happening
here is you've got multiple

00:53:02.750 --> 00:53:05.713
pathways that are saying avoid light,

00:53:06.620 --> 00:53:09.810
reduce your amount of behavior, heat up,

00:53:09.810 --> 00:53:11.250
all the things that are making you sick.

00:53:11.250 --> 00:53:14.670
This is sickness behavior,
and it's going from your body

00:53:14.670 --> 00:53:18.090
to your mind to make
you do the right thing.

00:53:18.090 --> 00:53:20.600
Now there's also a slow pathway

00:53:20.600 --> 00:53:23.120
that's purely mediated by the blood,

00:53:23.120 --> 00:53:24.730
so-called humoral factors.

00:53:24.730 --> 00:53:25.700
Not 'cause they're funny,

00:53:25.700 --> 00:53:28.760
but humoral factors are
factors of the blood.

00:53:28.760 --> 00:53:33.760
As you have an infection
for many hours or days,

00:53:34.580 --> 00:53:38.315
the amount of IL-6 and IL-1

00:53:38.315 --> 00:53:41.820
and tumor necrosis factor and
other inflammatory cytokines

00:53:41.820 --> 00:53:45.310
is starting to increase
such that the total amount

00:53:45.310 --> 00:53:47.420
in your circulation gets high enough

00:53:47.420 --> 00:53:49.790
and is communicated to the brain.

00:53:49.790 --> 00:53:52.740
And it tends to enter the brain through

00:53:52.740 --> 00:53:55.250
a particular type of tissue
that's really interesting

00:53:55.250 --> 00:53:58.950
called choroid, C-H-O-R-O-I-D.

00:53:58.950 --> 00:54:00.700
Choroid is really interesting.

00:54:00.700 --> 00:54:03.150
It's kind of this fluffy tissue

00:54:03.150 --> 00:54:04.300
that sits in your ventricles.

00:54:04.300 --> 00:54:06.200
The ventricles are the
spaces in your brain,

00:54:06.200 --> 00:54:08.140
and the spaces in your
brain have what's called

00:54:08.140 --> 00:54:10.020
cerebral spinal fluid in them.

00:54:10.020 --> 00:54:11.150
The cerebral spinal fluid contains

00:54:11.150 --> 00:54:12.430
a number of important things,

00:54:12.430 --> 00:54:16.130
but the choroid starts
releasing and responding

00:54:16.130 --> 00:54:19.690
to these cytokines, the
inflammatory cytokines,

00:54:19.690 --> 00:54:23.360
and then the brain actually
starts to experience

00:54:23.360 --> 00:54:27.380
all sorts of changes in terms
of inflammation to neurons,

00:54:27.380 --> 00:54:29.090
your memory tends to get poor,

00:54:29.090 --> 00:54:31.340
your cognition tends to get poor.

00:54:31.340 --> 00:54:34.030
These are transient things most often.

00:54:34.030 --> 00:54:35.600
Eventually these things will pass,

00:54:35.600 --> 00:54:37.020
but this is deep into sickness

00:54:37.020 --> 00:54:38.390
when you're really feeling lousy.

00:54:38.390 --> 00:54:39.920
You can't read, you can't watch a movie,

00:54:39.920 --> 00:54:40.753
you can't do anything.

00:54:40.753 --> 00:54:42.980
So if you ever get sick and you just can't

00:54:42.980 --> 00:54:44.660
be bothered by anything,

00:54:44.660 --> 00:54:47.420
it's probably because you've
had that fast response

00:54:47.420 --> 00:54:50.360
from the body and you've
also had the slower response

00:54:50.360 --> 00:54:52.940
where you literally have a
set of tissues in your brain

00:54:52.940 --> 00:54:56.300
that are sending out these
inflammatory signals.

00:54:56.300 --> 00:54:58.920
And now your whole brain
is starting to cope,

00:54:58.920 --> 00:55:00.920
or is trying to cope with this infection.

00:55:00.920 --> 00:55:03.320
So you've got a slow
pathway and a fast pathway.

00:55:05.010 --> 00:55:06.530
That all sounds really terrible.

00:55:06.530 --> 00:55:10.070
So, now, I'd like to talk
about what you can do to reduce

00:55:10.070 --> 00:55:12.550
the probability of getting sick.

00:55:12.550 --> 00:55:16.630
And there are actually
things that one can do

00:55:16.630 --> 00:55:19.160
as you start to get sick
and once you're sick,

00:55:19.160 --> 00:55:23.350
to accelerate the healing
process by flipping the equation.

00:55:23.350 --> 00:55:26.240
Up until now we've been
talking about how the body

00:55:26.240 --> 00:55:28.610
activates certain areas
in the brain to create

00:55:28.610 --> 00:55:30.960
sickness behavior that's
very much like depression.

00:55:30.960 --> 00:55:32.630
You're probably all familiar
with this from anytime

00:55:32.630 --> 00:55:34.790
you've had a cold or a flu
or something really lousy

00:55:34.790 --> 00:55:35.930
or an injury.

00:55:35.930 --> 00:55:40.530
Now, let's flip the equation
and ask what can we do

00:55:40.530 --> 00:55:43.040
with our nervous system
in order to enhance

00:55:43.040 --> 00:55:45.940
the function of our immune
system in order to be able

00:55:45.940 --> 00:55:49.590
to heal and recover from
illness and injury more quickly.

00:55:49.590 --> 00:55:52.650
So let's say you are in that
unfortunate circumstance

00:55:52.650 --> 00:55:57.040
of waking up one day or coming home,

00:55:57.040 --> 00:55:59.990
and you've got that tickle in your throat,

00:55:59.990 --> 00:56:01.520
or when you breathe,

00:56:01.520 --> 00:56:03.800
your nasal passages
don't feel the same way.

00:56:03.800 --> 00:56:04.860
You've got a little bit of a headache.

00:56:04.860 --> 00:56:06.210
You're feeling kind of off.

00:56:07.120 --> 00:56:08.360
We all know what we should do.

00:56:08.360 --> 00:56:12.090
We should all hydrate, drink
some water and go to sleep.

00:56:12.090 --> 00:56:14.380
Right, that's we are all told,

00:56:14.380 --> 00:56:18.210
but there are actually things
that you can actively do

00:56:18.210 --> 00:56:22.700
in order to get your immune
system to deploy a more robust

00:56:22.700 --> 00:56:27.700
response at that early phase
of potential infection.

00:56:29.600 --> 00:56:31.793
Let's focus first on the rest component.

00:56:32.670 --> 00:56:34.990
Yes, of course we are all
told that we should take

00:56:34.990 --> 00:56:36.790
a hot shower and go to sleep,

00:56:36.790 --> 00:56:38.720
and get nine or 10 hours of sleep.

00:56:38.720 --> 00:56:42.320
But there's an interesting
way of looking at sleep,

00:56:42.320 --> 00:56:47.130
specifically for its role in
enhancing the immune system.

00:56:47.130 --> 00:56:49.790
And there's a wonderful review,

00:56:49.790 --> 00:56:54.250
I'll put the review in the
captions that looked specifically

00:56:54.250 --> 00:56:59.250
at the literature surrounding
sleep that is different

00:56:59.270 --> 00:57:02.750
because it occurs in support
of the immune system.

00:57:02.750 --> 00:57:04.180
So normally when we go to sleep,

00:57:04.180 --> 00:57:05.660
we have slow-wave sleep predominantly

00:57:05.660 --> 00:57:06.960
in the early phase of the night,

00:57:06.960 --> 00:57:09.190
and then over time as we
sleep longer and longer,

00:57:09.190 --> 00:57:11.360
we get more so-called REM,
rapid eye movement sleep.

00:57:11.360 --> 00:57:14.250
I talked all about this
on the episodes on sleep.

00:57:14.250 --> 00:57:16.250
Of course you have slow-wave
sleep and REM sleep

00:57:16.250 --> 00:57:17.490
throughout the night always,

00:57:17.490 --> 00:57:19.010
but it's the fraction of slow-wave sleep

00:57:19.010 --> 00:57:20.620
to REM sleep that shifts,

00:57:20.620 --> 00:57:22.923
and they have different
functions, et cetera.

00:57:23.820 --> 00:57:27.090
There is some evidence
that the sleep associated

00:57:27.090 --> 00:57:31.710
with an infection, in particular,
early stage of infection,

00:57:31.710 --> 00:57:36.280
is associated with elevated
levels of serotonin in the brain

00:57:36.280 --> 00:57:39.170
that either through an adaptive mechanism

00:57:39.170 --> 00:57:41.570
or for whatever reason,
the neurons in the brain

00:57:42.544 --> 00:57:44.260
of the so-called raphe nucleus start

00:57:44.260 --> 00:57:46.423
releasing more serotonin.

00:57:47.620 --> 00:57:50.320
And that serotonin and
its related pathways

00:57:50.320 --> 00:57:53.870
can help enhance some of
the immune system function

00:57:53.870 --> 00:57:56.190
that could combat the infection.

00:57:56.190 --> 00:57:59.590
There is starting to be some data,

00:57:59.590 --> 00:58:01.620
and I emphasize starting because it's not

00:58:01.620 --> 00:58:03.520
a very robust literature yet,

00:58:03.520 --> 00:58:06.560
looking at whether or not
supplementing precursors

00:58:06.560 --> 00:58:09.340
to serotonin like 5-HTP,

00:58:09.340 --> 00:58:12.520
which can be taken in a supplement form

00:58:12.520 --> 00:58:17.520
or consuming foods that
increase serotonin naturally.

00:58:17.560 --> 00:58:19.740
So these would be any foods that contain

00:58:19.740 --> 00:58:20.830
high levels of tryptophan.

00:58:20.830 --> 00:58:22.000
You can look up what those are.

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:25.200
So, white meat turkey, for instance,

00:58:25.200 --> 00:58:28.530
certain complex carbohydrates can often

00:58:28.530 --> 00:58:30.490
be rich with tryptophan.

00:58:30.490 --> 00:58:33.080
That consuming those foods can enhance

00:58:33.080 --> 00:58:34.947
the amount of serotonin
that's available in the brain

00:58:34.947 --> 00:58:37.970
and blood and thereby
lead to the particular

00:58:37.970 --> 00:58:41.470
quality of sleep that
allows for more deep healing

00:58:41.470 --> 00:58:43.280
or for when I say deep healing,

00:58:43.280 --> 00:58:46.210
I mean for a more robust immune response.

00:58:46.210 --> 00:58:49.920
Now, again, those are still emerging data.

00:58:49.920 --> 00:58:52.070
What is very clear, however,

00:58:52.070 --> 00:58:54.560
is that during sleep and in particular,

00:58:54.560 --> 00:58:56.940
during sleep that's associated
with the early stage

00:58:56.940 --> 00:58:59.660
of any kind of viral
or bacterial infection,

00:58:59.660 --> 00:59:03.720
the so-called glymphatic
system is much more active

00:59:03.720 --> 00:59:05.060
than it would be normally.

00:59:05.060 --> 00:59:06.450
What's the glymphatic system?

00:59:06.450 --> 00:59:07.830
The glymphatic system is actually

00:59:07.830 --> 00:59:10.540
a relatively recent discovery.

00:59:10.540 --> 00:59:14.050
I mentioned lymph and the
lymphatic system earlier,

00:59:14.050 --> 00:59:18.550
the glymphatic system with a
G, is a system in the brain

00:59:18.550 --> 00:59:22.270
by which debris that
accumulates throughout the day,

00:59:22.270 --> 00:59:25.730
but in particular, debris that
accumulates under conditions

00:59:25.730 --> 00:59:29.860
of neuroinflammation and
inflammation of the body,

00:59:29.860 --> 00:59:33.130
is cleared out or is
washed out of the brain.

00:59:33.130 --> 00:59:36.290
And the activity of this glymphatic system

00:59:36.290 --> 00:59:39.390
is extremely important for the recovery

00:59:39.390 --> 00:59:41.810
from infection of any kind.

00:59:41.810 --> 00:59:45.280
And it's now becoming clear,
is important for recovery

00:59:45.280 --> 00:59:46.860
from traumatic head injury,

00:59:46.860 --> 00:59:48.913
and maybe even from psychological trauma.

00:59:49.760 --> 00:59:52.720
So, the glymphatic system can
be thought of more or less

00:59:52.720 --> 00:59:55.200
as a plumbing system that
runs through the ventricles,

00:59:55.200 --> 00:59:58.060
but also mainly through
the lining that sits

00:59:58.060 --> 00:59:59.710
between the brain and the skull

00:59:59.710 --> 01:00:03.050
and some of the other tissues
and things of that sort.

01:00:03.050 --> 01:00:05.200
The choroid is involved as well.

01:00:05.200 --> 01:00:07.250
Brain imaging reveals
the glymphatic system

01:00:07.250 --> 01:00:08.690
is very active during deep sleep.

01:00:08.690 --> 01:00:11.440
And there's this kind of wash
out of the glymphatic system.

01:00:11.440 --> 01:00:14.490
And I am aware of some
studies that are ongoing now

01:00:14.490 --> 01:00:18.260
where augmenting the serotonin
system through either

01:00:18.260 --> 01:00:21.700
supplementation of tryptophan or 5-HTP

01:00:21.700 --> 01:00:24.630
or even serotonin itself,
these are laboratory studies,

01:00:24.630 --> 01:00:27.210
is being looked at for
its capacity to increase

01:00:27.210 --> 01:00:30.020
the amount of circulation
in the glymphatic system.

01:00:30.020 --> 01:00:32.900
And the idea is that it might,
and I want to underscore might,

01:00:32.900 --> 01:00:36.690
potentially lead to more
rapid recovery from injury

01:00:36.690 --> 01:00:40.080
and illness and potentially
ramp up, if you will,

01:00:40.080 --> 01:00:41.870
the activity of the immune system.

01:00:41.870 --> 01:00:44.260
So, it essentially is a
ramping up of the activity

01:00:44.260 --> 01:00:45.350
of the immune system.

01:00:45.350 --> 01:00:48.690
Now, regardless of whether
or not you decide to,

01:00:48.690 --> 01:00:52.100
for instance, supplement with
5-HTP before sleep or not,

01:00:52.100 --> 01:00:54.310
I'll talk about what that
might look like in a moment,

01:00:54.310 --> 01:00:56.480
there is a way that you
can increase the activity

01:00:56.480 --> 01:01:00.200
of your glymphatic system
under normal circumstances.

01:01:00.200 --> 01:01:02.700
Because of the mechanics
of the glymphatic system,

01:01:03.610 --> 01:01:06.740
it turns out that if
you elevate your heels

01:01:06.740 --> 01:01:10.050
by about 12 degrees, it
doesn't have to be exactly 12,

01:01:10.050 --> 01:01:12.040
as you sleep by putting
maybe a rolled pillow

01:01:12.040 --> 01:01:13.840
or two pillows underneath your feet,

01:01:13.840 --> 01:01:17.500
by having the head below your legs.

01:01:17.500 --> 01:01:20.130
It seems that there's
more glymphatic washout

01:01:20.130 --> 01:01:22.000
or clearance during sleep.

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:23.630
And this is without taking any compound

01:01:23.630 --> 01:01:25.190
to adjust the serotonin system.

01:01:25.190 --> 01:01:27.470
So I would say if you're not feeling well,

01:01:27.470 --> 01:01:28.660
yes, take the hot shower.

01:01:28.660 --> 01:01:30.670
Yes, get into bed and go to sleep,

01:01:30.670 --> 01:01:32.630
but elevate your feet to try and increase

01:01:32.630 --> 01:01:34.693
the activity of the glymphatic system.

01:01:36.510 --> 01:01:41.140
Some might even consider
that if you have to be awake,

01:01:41.140 --> 01:01:42.470
that you might want to be awake

01:01:42.470 --> 01:01:45.040
with your feet elevated above your head.

01:01:45.040 --> 01:01:48.010
Now that might not be
practical for the workplace,

01:01:48.010 --> 01:01:50.940
but it might be practical for
a short nap during the day

01:01:50.940 --> 01:01:51.820
or something of that sort.

01:01:51.820 --> 01:01:54.310
The glymphatic system is not
just active during sleep.

01:01:54.310 --> 01:01:56.460
It's also active during
certain phases of waking,

01:01:56.460 --> 01:02:00.020
in particular when we are in
a deep state of relaxation.

01:02:00.020 --> 01:02:03.240
So as many of you probably
know I'm a big proponent

01:02:03.240 --> 01:02:06.020
of self-hypnosis because of the quality

01:02:06.020 --> 01:02:07.300
scientific literature on this.

01:02:07.300 --> 01:02:08.880
If you're interested in self-hypnosis,

01:02:08.880 --> 01:02:12.000
you can go to Reverie, R-E-V-E-R-I.com.

