Reverie is a cost-free
app for Apple and Android

01:02:16.020 --> 01:02:18.140
that was developed by my
colleague, David Spiegel,

01:02:18.140 --> 01:02:20.410
and others at the Stanford
University School of Medicine,

01:02:20.410 --> 01:02:23.290
based on quality studies
and peer reviewed data,

01:02:23.290 --> 01:02:26.830
showing that deep states
of relaxation can be used

01:02:26.830 --> 01:02:28.990
to improve pain management,

01:02:28.990 --> 01:02:30.507
improve transition time to sleep,

01:02:30.507 --> 01:02:32.450
and a number of other things.

01:02:32.450 --> 01:02:35.900
You can select the
various sort of outcomes

01:02:35.900 --> 01:02:38.130
that you're seeking using Reverie.

01:02:38.130 --> 01:02:40.130
It's a great thing especially for people

01:02:40.130 --> 01:02:42.360
that are challenged with
meditation could use,

01:02:42.360 --> 01:02:43.590
because you just listened to the script.

01:02:43.590 --> 01:02:45.120
It involves deep relaxation.

01:02:45.120 --> 01:02:48.870
I would suggest using that
script, or the script for sleep,

01:02:48.870 --> 01:02:50.840
but with feet elevated
to increase activity

01:02:50.840 --> 01:02:52.070
of the glymphatic system.

01:02:52.070 --> 01:02:56.060
Now, if you do decide
that you want to test out

01:02:56.060 --> 01:02:58.210
this serotonin hypothesis on your own,

01:02:58.210 --> 01:02:59.570
obviously check with a doctor.

01:02:59.570 --> 01:03:00.960
I'm not a doctor, I'm a professor.

01:03:00.960 --> 01:03:02.770
So, I'm professing things,
not suggesting things,

01:03:02.770 --> 01:03:06.650
but 5-HTP is a supplement
that I've talked about before

01:03:06.650 --> 01:03:10.390
on this podcast that I
actually do not recommend

01:03:10.390 --> 01:03:12.420
for most people for sake of sleep,

01:03:12.420 --> 01:03:15.970
because it can disrupt the
normal architecture of sleep

01:03:15.970 --> 01:03:18.580
and create a deep sleep
early in the night,

01:03:18.580 --> 01:03:20.650
and then a spontaneous
waking with some trouble

01:03:20.650 --> 01:03:21.810
to get back to sleep.

01:03:21.810 --> 01:03:23.880
And that's because of the
way that the serotonin system

01:03:23.880 --> 01:03:25.950
and the melatonin system interact.

01:03:25.950 --> 01:03:28.920
However, under conditions
where one is feeling

01:03:28.920 --> 01:03:30.240
like they might have an infection

01:03:30.240 --> 01:03:32.580
or an early stage of illness,

01:03:32.580 --> 01:03:35.820
in that case, 5-HTP might
be a useful supplement

01:03:35.820 --> 01:03:38.250
in order to access these states of sleep

01:03:38.250 --> 01:03:39.750
that are not typical.

01:03:39.750 --> 01:03:42.860
They're not the typical deep
sleep that you would achieve

01:03:42.860 --> 01:03:43.920
when you're feeling healthy.

01:03:43.920 --> 01:03:47.180
These are states of sleep
that are specifically there

01:03:47.180 --> 01:03:50.460
in order to try and repair
some of the immune system

01:03:50.460 --> 01:03:52.610
related inflammation that's occurring.

01:03:52.610 --> 01:03:55.750
If you'd like to explore
the 5-HTP approach

01:03:55.750 --> 01:03:57.830
and you feel it's right and safe for you,

01:03:57.830 --> 01:03:59.580
and you've talked to your doctor,

01:03:59.580 --> 01:04:03.460
it's 300 to 500 milligrams
taken about 30 to 60 minutes

01:04:03.460 --> 01:04:06.400
before going to sleep for the night.

01:04:06.400 --> 01:04:08.620
That's the typical protocol.

01:04:08.620 --> 01:04:13.620
Not incidentally,
increasing serotonin is also

01:04:13.940 --> 01:04:17.130
one typical approach for the
treatment of major depression.

01:04:17.130 --> 01:04:19.950
This is the basis for things like SSRIs,

01:04:19.950 --> 01:04:21.880
selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors,

01:04:21.880 --> 01:04:26.470
like Prozac and Zoloft, and so forth.

01:04:26.470 --> 01:04:29.910
The 5-HTP approach is
a much milder approach

01:04:29.910 --> 01:04:32.550
than prescription drug, of course,

01:04:32.550 --> 01:04:35.050
but will allow more serotonin

01:04:35.050 --> 01:04:37.430
to be synthesized and/or released.

01:04:37.430 --> 01:04:40.520
Now, for those of you that are
interested in learning more

01:04:40.520 --> 01:04:43.170
about the glymphatic system,
it's a fascinating system,

01:04:43.170 --> 01:04:44.870
and you might want to do a deep dive there

01:04:44.870 --> 01:04:46.410
in terms of the behavioral protocols,

01:04:46.410 --> 01:04:47.243
and what's known about it,

01:04:47.243 --> 01:04:49.947
there's a wonderful article called

01:04:49.947 --> 01:04:52.610
"The Glymphatic System:
A Beginner's Guide."

01:04:52.610 --> 01:04:55.040
This is a scientific article.

01:04:55.040 --> 01:04:59.550
The first author is Jessen is
the last name, J-E-S-S-E-N.

01:04:59.550 --> 01:05:02.010
If you put in "Jessen,
The Glymphatic System:

01:05:02.010 --> 01:05:03.990
A Beginner's Guide," you
can access the full length

01:05:03.990 --> 01:05:05.340
manuscript easily online.

01:05:05.340 --> 01:05:08.290
It'll show up immediately in your search.

01:05:08.290 --> 01:05:11.170
And in a really interesting way,

01:05:11.170 --> 01:05:14.520
the glymphatic system
has now also been tied

01:05:14.520 --> 01:05:17.250
to the iron deposition system.

01:05:17.250 --> 01:05:19.220
Earlier we were talking
about iron and how,

01:05:19.220 --> 01:05:21.720
of course, getting enough
dietary iron is important,

01:05:21.720 --> 01:05:23.980
but if levels of iron are too high

01:05:23.980 --> 01:05:27.170
it isn't good for a number of reasons.

01:05:27.170 --> 01:05:28.960
There's a very interesting article

01:05:28.960 --> 01:05:30.647
that just came out last year called

01:05:30.647 --> 01:05:34.610
"Dysfunction of the glymphatic
system might be related

01:05:34.610 --> 01:05:38.020
to iron deposition in
the normal aging brain."

01:05:38.020 --> 01:05:39.960
So, we're starting to see these links

01:05:39.960 --> 01:05:42.670
between iron levels being too high,

01:05:42.670 --> 01:05:47.670
the glymphatic system not being
active enough and so forth,

01:05:47.960 --> 01:05:50.570
leading to sickness
behavior, inflammation,

01:05:50.570 --> 01:05:54.120
and maybe even damage to
neurons associated with aging.

01:05:54.120 --> 01:05:57.060
We can flip that on its
head and say that increasing

01:05:57.060 --> 01:05:58.950
the activity of the glymphatic system,

01:05:58.950 --> 01:06:01.480
feet elevated during deep sleep,

01:06:01.480 --> 01:06:06.183
maybe even feet elevated
above the head while awake,

01:06:07.370 --> 01:06:09.430
during a nap or doing a Reverie script

01:06:09.430 --> 01:06:11.430
once a day or something of that sort,

01:06:11.430 --> 01:06:13.790
could increase the activity
of the glymphatic system,

01:06:13.790 --> 01:06:18.790
lowering iron to a point
that's probably below

01:06:18.920 --> 01:06:22.760
the typical intake during
periods of infection,

01:06:22.760 --> 01:06:24.880
perhaps, I should say,

01:06:24.880 --> 01:06:27.520
can enhance the glymphatic
system and vice versa.

01:06:27.520 --> 01:06:30.510
And then you've got this specialized sleep

01:06:30.510 --> 01:06:32.750
that's related to sickness behavior

01:06:32.750 --> 01:06:35.520
that seems to have heightened
levels of serotonin

01:06:35.520 --> 01:06:38.867
that might be augmented
by ingesting 5-HTP.

01:06:42.970 --> 01:06:44.940
Again, not on a regular basis.

01:06:44.940 --> 01:06:47.100
I don't suggest that people take compounds

01:06:47.100 --> 01:06:49.040
that increase serotonin
unless it's prescribed

01:06:49.040 --> 01:06:50.577
to you for depression or something,

01:06:50.577 --> 01:06:55.230
but not doing by supplement
with tryptophan or 5-HTP

01:06:55.230 --> 01:06:57.310
on a regular basis, but
only under conditions

01:06:57.310 --> 01:07:00.120
where as I mentioned, you
might be starting to feel sick

01:07:00.120 --> 01:07:01.190
or you're coming down with something,

01:07:01.190 --> 01:07:03.550
or you're combating
some sort of infection.

01:07:03.550 --> 01:07:06.720
So if we consider the
advice that we typically get

01:07:06.720 --> 01:07:08.610
when we're not feeling
well of take a hot shower,

01:07:08.610 --> 01:07:10.410
get into bed and go to sleep,

01:07:10.410 --> 01:07:14.470
and we've now touched on
ways to potentially increase

01:07:14.470 --> 01:07:16.490
the efficacy of the sleep part through

01:07:16.490 --> 01:07:18.520
the glymphatic and the serotonin system.

01:07:18.520 --> 01:07:20.140
What about the take a hot shower part?

01:07:20.140 --> 01:07:20.973
Is that good advice?

01:07:20.973 --> 01:07:21.830
Well, it turns out it is,

01:07:21.830 --> 01:07:24.080
and there's actually a
way to do even better.

01:07:25.100 --> 01:07:27.810
There's a study, a very interesting study,

01:07:27.810 --> 01:07:29.680
the title reveals where
I'm going with this,

01:07:29.680 --> 01:07:33.550
it's "Effect of a single
Finnish sauna session

01:07:33.550 --> 01:07:36.300
on white blood cell profile
and cortisol levels."

01:07:36.300 --> 01:07:38.480
In this case, it was done in
athletes and non-athletes,

01:07:38.480 --> 01:07:40.380
which is kind of nice.

01:07:40.380 --> 01:07:44.270
This involves taking
athletes and non-athletes

01:07:44.270 --> 01:07:46.050
and exposing them to sauna.

01:07:46.050 --> 01:07:47.770
It wasn't particularly hot.

01:07:47.770 --> 01:07:49.940
It was 96 degrees, which isn't cool,

01:07:49.940 --> 01:07:50.990
but it's not really hot.

01:07:50.990 --> 01:07:53.900
Nowadays you hear about people
doing very, very hot sauna.

01:07:53.900 --> 01:07:55.530
The humidity of the sauna,
if you want to know,

01:07:55.530 --> 01:07:56.870
is 15 plus or minus 3%.

01:07:56.870 --> 01:08:00.640
But basically what they found
was that just one 15 minutes

01:08:00.640 --> 01:08:02.130
sauna session could really increase

01:08:02.130 --> 01:08:05.570
white blood cell profiles and
could adjust cortisol levels

01:08:05.570 --> 01:08:08.780
in ways that were beneficial
for combating infection.

01:08:08.780 --> 01:08:11.110
And now there are many
other studies like this.

01:08:11.110 --> 01:08:13.340
Now, this should immediately
make sense based on

01:08:13.340 --> 01:08:14.590
what we said before about fever;

01:08:14.590 --> 01:08:17.810
heating up can actually
help combat infection.

01:08:17.810 --> 01:08:18.960
But for those of you that have listened

01:08:18.960 --> 01:08:20.563
to the episodes on temperature,

01:08:20.563 --> 01:08:22.950
what you probably know is
that when you get into a sauna

01:08:22.950 --> 01:08:24.350
or any kind of hot environment,

01:08:24.350 --> 01:08:26.240
your body is also going to be actively

01:08:26.240 --> 01:08:28.210
pushing to cool itself off.

01:08:28.210 --> 01:08:30.750
So, there's probably an increase in heat,

01:08:30.750 --> 01:08:32.010
there is an increase in heating,

01:08:32.010 --> 01:08:34.360
but then afterwards
your body will cool off,

01:08:34.360 --> 01:08:36.460
maybe even with a dip below baseline.

01:08:36.460 --> 01:08:38.560
I do want to provide a cautionary note

01:08:38.560 --> 01:08:40.920
that if you are already running a fever,

01:08:40.920 --> 01:08:43.290
getting into a sauna could
take your body temperature

01:08:43.290 --> 01:08:44.770
into dangerously high levels,

01:08:44.770 --> 01:08:46.500
dangerously meaning you can kill neurons.

01:08:46.500 --> 01:08:48.990
And once you kill neurons,
they do not come back.

01:08:48.990 --> 01:08:50.740
So, please don't kill your neurons.

01:08:51.780 --> 01:08:53.930
I don't recommend getting into a sauna

01:08:53.930 --> 01:08:55.220
if you're already running a fever.

01:08:55.220 --> 01:08:57.900
So this would be something
to do at the initial stage

01:08:57.900 --> 01:09:00.380
of an infection or if you're
feeling a little bit off.

01:09:00.380 --> 01:09:04.070
So this is kind of a ramping
up or a super protocol

01:09:04.070 --> 01:09:06.390
of the typical advice of take
a hot shower and get into bed.

01:09:06.390 --> 01:09:07.223
That is good advice.

01:09:07.223 --> 01:09:09.920
Now we're talking about a hot sauna,

01:09:09.920 --> 01:09:12.440
probably showering off
and then getting into bed,

01:09:12.440 --> 01:09:14.370
maybe augmenting serotonin.

01:09:14.370 --> 01:09:16.570
I know many people don't
have access to sauna.

01:09:16.570 --> 01:09:19.640
So, in that case, a
very hot bath or shower,

01:09:19.640 --> 01:09:21.140
don't scald yourself, of course,

01:09:21.140 --> 01:09:23.640
but as hot as you can comfortably tolerate

01:09:23.640 --> 01:09:26.230
or right at that edge
of what you can tolerate

01:09:26.230 --> 01:09:27.400
would be a good idea.

01:09:27.400 --> 01:09:29.300
Some people I've heard are creating saunas

01:09:29.300 --> 01:09:31.360
in their bathrooms by running hot water

01:09:31.360 --> 01:09:32.470
and creating a ton of steam.

01:09:32.470 --> 01:09:35.550
Anything that really heats you up,

01:09:35.550 --> 01:09:36.900
but not to dangerously high levels

01:09:36.900 --> 01:09:38.200
is going to be beneficial.

01:09:39.140 --> 01:09:41.283
If you have access to a sauna, terrific.

01:09:42.300 --> 01:09:44.873
This again was only 15 minutes.

01:09:45.730 --> 01:09:47.830
They'd had a cool off session.

01:09:47.830 --> 01:09:50.210
Would you get more of an increase?

01:09:50.210 --> 01:09:51.620
People always want to know
if you did it twice as much,

01:09:51.620 --> 01:09:53.420
would you get twice an increase?

01:09:53.420 --> 01:09:54.810
Those data don't really exist yet.

01:09:54.810 --> 01:09:57.130
However, if you are
interested in maximizing

01:09:57.130 --> 01:09:58.640
the effects of sauna,

01:09:58.640 --> 01:10:01.580
it is clear that a cool
off period is important.

01:10:01.580 --> 01:10:04.350
So it's not that a 15
minute sauna is good,

01:10:04.350 --> 01:10:05.910
and a 30 minute sauna is better.

01:10:05.910 --> 01:10:09.120
If you are going to take
that route of exploring more,

01:10:09.120 --> 01:10:12.420
it does seem that doing a
15 minute heating period

01:10:12.420 --> 01:10:14.650
followed by a five to 10
minute cooling period,

01:10:14.650 --> 01:10:18.500
and then getting back into
the heat can be beneficial.

01:10:18.500 --> 01:10:19.620
And this is interesting.

01:10:19.620 --> 01:10:24.620
It gets to the mechanisms by
which the hypothalamus areas,

01:10:24.710 --> 01:10:26.020
the areas of the hypothalamus, that is,

01:10:26.020 --> 01:10:28.250
that generate increases in body heat,

01:10:28.250 --> 01:10:32.600
the activation of those
neurons occurs as you heat up

01:10:32.600 --> 01:10:35.550
and then were you to just stay
in that heated environment,

01:10:35.550 --> 01:10:37.620
they would actually shut
off and some other neurons

01:10:37.620 --> 01:10:39.680
would be handling the job so to speak.

01:10:39.680 --> 01:10:42.230
But by getting in and out
of the heated environment,

01:10:42.230 --> 01:10:45.460
you actually force that
system to send repeated pulses

01:10:45.460 --> 01:10:49.890
of these cortisol lowering
and white cell stimulating

01:10:49.890 --> 01:10:51.360
signals to the body.

01:10:51.360 --> 01:10:52.977
Some of you have probably
heard the phrase,

01:10:52.977 --> 01:10:55.327
"feed a fever, starve a cold."

01:10:56.170 --> 01:10:57.960
I don't know who first said that.

01:10:57.960 --> 01:11:01.410
I couldn't find the
citation, but we hear this.

01:11:01.410 --> 01:11:05.397
And we can speculate that
the reason that phrase,

01:11:05.397 --> 01:11:08.170
"feed a fever, starve a cold" came to be

01:11:08.170 --> 01:11:10.800
is because of the adaptive
function of fever,

01:11:10.800 --> 01:11:14.360
that increases in body
temperature make it challenging

01:11:14.360 --> 01:11:19.160
for intruding viruses
and bacteria to survive.

01:11:19.160 --> 01:11:22.100
Even though, of course, highly
elevated body temperatures

01:11:22.100 --> 01:11:24.633
pose a danger to the
host organism, to you.

01:11:27.260 --> 01:11:31.030
Feeding, eating does cause an
increase in body temperature

01:11:31.030 --> 01:11:33.480
through the so-called
thermogenic effect of food.

01:11:33.480 --> 01:11:36.720
So I can understand the
logic of feed a fever.

01:11:36.720 --> 01:11:38.700
It would mean that when you have a fever,

01:11:38.700 --> 01:11:41.300
it's your body's natural
attempt to heat up

01:11:41.300 --> 01:11:44.150
and kill some invading thing.

01:11:44.150 --> 01:11:46.180
And by eating, you would further increase

01:11:46.180 --> 01:11:47.930
your body temperature.

01:11:47.930 --> 01:11:51.223
Why you would want to starve
a cold, I don't know, however.

01:11:52.330 --> 01:11:55.290
Maybe it's because when your
nasal passages are congested,

01:11:55.290 --> 01:11:58.070
it's uncomfortable to eat
or something of that sort.

01:11:58.070 --> 01:12:00.220
So the feet of fever
part makes sense to me,

01:12:00.220 --> 01:12:02.900
the starve a cold part is
still mysterious to me.

01:12:02.900 --> 01:12:06.870
I couldn't find any logical
reason why that would be good.

01:12:06.870 --> 01:12:09.830
There are communities out
there that believe that fasting

01:12:09.830 --> 01:12:14.763
is a viable way to combat
certain types of infection.

01:12:16.000 --> 01:12:18.380
Fasting, in particular, prolonged fasts,

01:12:18.380 --> 01:12:21.540
do increase the amount of adrenaline,

01:12:21.540 --> 01:12:24.310
also called epinephrin,
in the brain and body.

01:12:24.310 --> 01:12:27.930
And as we'll next explain, epinephrin,

01:12:27.930 --> 01:12:31.500
adrenaline does have a powerful effect on

01:12:31.500 --> 01:12:33.250
the various inflammatory cytokines

01:12:33.250 --> 01:12:35.370
and on the immune system in general.

01:12:35.370 --> 01:12:38.190
So, let's talk about a behavioral protocol

01:12:38.190 --> 01:12:40.700
that anyone can use; it
doesn't involve any equipment,

01:12:40.700 --> 01:12:43.700
you don't need a sauna, you
don't need anything at all,

01:12:43.700 --> 01:12:46.900
that has been demonstrated
in excellent peer reviewed

01:12:46.900 --> 01:12:49.970
research to enhance the
function of the immune system

01:12:49.970 --> 01:12:52.920
and actually allow people
to combat infection

01:12:52.920 --> 01:12:54.780
in very dramatic ways.

01:12:54.780 --> 01:12:58.900
Next, I'd like to do an
in-depth analysis of a study

01:12:58.900 --> 01:13:01.760
that has achieved some
prominence out there,

01:13:01.760 --> 01:13:05.100
not just in the scientific
literature, but on the internet,

01:13:05.100 --> 01:13:09.510
because it relates to how
particular types of breathing

01:13:09.510 --> 01:13:11.630
can impact the immune system

01:13:11.630 --> 01:13:14.650
and the ability to combat infection.

01:13:14.650 --> 01:13:16.277
The title of this paper is

01:13:16.277 --> 01:13:19.620
"Voluntary activation of the
sympathetic nervous system

01:13:19.620 --> 01:13:24.020
and attenuation of the innate
immune response in humans."

01:13:24.020 --> 01:13:26.170
This is a paper that
was published in PNAS,

01:13:27.340 --> 01:13:29.010
which is the Proceedings
of the National Academy

01:13:29.010 --> 01:13:30.130
of Sciences, USA.

01:13:30.130 --> 01:13:32.223
It's a very prestigious journal.

01:13:33.160 --> 01:13:34.780
For those of you that know PNAS,

01:13:34.780 --> 01:13:37.610
you know that there are certain
papers published in PNAS,

01:13:37.610 --> 01:13:39.410
or there used to be that
were not peer reviewed.

01:13:39.410 --> 01:13:41.340
In recent years, I think
all of them have moved

01:13:41.340 --> 01:13:42.320
to peer reviewed papers.

01:13:42.320 --> 01:13:46.360
So this is a peer reviewed,
very high quality study.

01:13:46.360 --> 01:13:50.170
And I just want to describe
the basic contour of the study.

01:13:50.170 --> 01:13:52.690
I'll explain the findings,
and then I want to go in-depth

01:13:52.690 --> 01:13:55.810
and explain the mechanistic
basis for these findings

01:13:55.810 --> 01:14:00.090
and the protocol that we can
all export from these findings.

01:14:00.090 --> 01:14:01.853
So, here we go.

01:14:02.820 --> 01:14:05.170
First of all, a couple of
terms so that everybody

01:14:05.170 --> 01:14:06.373
is on the same page.

01:14:07.420 --> 01:14:10.580
The sympathetic nervous
system is one division

01:14:10.580 --> 01:14:11.500
of our nervous system.

01:14:11.500 --> 01:14:14.720
It's a set of neurons down
the middle of our spinal cord

01:14:14.720 --> 01:14:19.530
and in our brain that generally
lead to a heightened state

01:14:19.530 --> 01:14:21.030
of arousal and alertness.

01:14:21.030 --> 01:14:23.550
It's associated with
epinephrin release in the brain

01:14:23.550 --> 01:14:25.680
and adrenaline release in the body.

01:14:25.680 --> 01:14:27.860
It's the so-called fight or flight system

01:14:27.860 --> 01:14:29.440
when it's really active,

01:14:29.440 --> 01:14:33.273
but it's the system that's
active when we are wide awake.

01:14:34.450 --> 01:14:37.850
And we already talked about
the innate immune system.

01:14:37.850 --> 01:14:40.950
That's that first line of
defense after the skin barrier,

01:14:40.950 --> 01:14:44.670
of course, whereby some
infection comes into the body

01:14:44.670 --> 01:14:48.690
and there's this rapid response
of increasing inflammation.

01:14:48.690 --> 01:14:52.070
And that's also about the time
that you first feel lousy.

01:14:52.070 --> 01:14:52.903
So when you start to feel like,

01:14:52.903 --> 01:14:54.170
"ugh, I think I've got something.

01:14:54.170 --> 01:14:55.670
I don't feel right, a headache.

01:14:55.670 --> 01:14:57.010
I feel nauseous.

01:14:57.010 --> 01:14:57.870
I'm heating up.

01:14:57.870 --> 01:14:58.710
I don't feel good."

01:14:58.710 --> 01:15:02.083
That's the innate immune
system kicking in.

01:15:02.920 --> 01:15:05.270
So what they did in this study,

01:15:05.270 --> 01:15:07.740
and by the way, I should say they,

01:15:07.740 --> 01:15:10.880
this first author is Kox, K-O-X,

01:15:10.880 --> 01:15:15.570
last author, last name
Pickkers, P-I-C-K-K-E-R-S.

01:15:15.570 --> 01:15:20.200
What they did was they
exposed human subjects

01:15:20.200 --> 01:15:21.553
to an endotoxin.

01:15:22.830 --> 01:15:25.790
In other words, they
injected people with E. coli,

01:15:25.790 --> 01:15:29.430
which is a bacteria which makes people,

01:15:29.430 --> 01:15:30.950
all people feel terrible.

01:15:30.950 --> 01:15:34.700
Makes you nauseous,
fever, vomiting, diarrhea,

01:15:34.700 --> 01:15:36.610
it's very unpleasant, okay?

01:15:36.610 --> 01:15:39.110
These people voluntarily
signed up for this study.

01:15:40.080 --> 01:15:42.680
However, some of the
subjects in this study

01:15:43.630 --> 01:15:48.630
performed a behavioral protocol
that can best be described

01:15:48.710 --> 01:15:50.730
as cyclic hyperventilation.

01:15:50.730 --> 01:15:53.210
My lab works on these types
of breathing protocols.

01:15:53.210 --> 01:15:54.670
This is not work that my lab did,

01:15:54.670 --> 01:15:57.840
but basically subjects hyperventilate,

01:15:57.840 --> 01:16:00.140
followed by breath
retention, by breath holds,

01:16:00.140 --> 01:16:02.220
and I'll explain exactly what they did.

01:16:02.220 --> 01:16:05.610
They also looked at other
forms of behavioral protocols,

01:16:05.610 --> 01:16:07.010
but let's focus on that one.

01:16:08.390 --> 01:16:10.820
So, they're comparing
controls that do just sort

01:16:10.820 --> 01:16:13.060
of a basic meditation
versus people that do

01:16:13.060 --> 01:16:15.833
this intense breathing
followed by some breath holds.

01:16:16.770 --> 01:16:19.447
I'm just paraphrasing here,
in the intervention group,

01:16:19.447 --> 01:16:20.510
the breathing group,

01:16:20.510 --> 01:16:24.580
plasma levels of
anti-inflammatory cytokine IL-10,

01:16:24.580 --> 01:16:27.750
so this is a cytokine that
is lowers inflammation,

01:16:27.750 --> 01:16:32.143
increased after endotoxin administration.

01:16:33.100 --> 01:16:35.840
And that was triggered by an increase

01:16:35.840 --> 01:16:37.090
in epinephrin and adrenaline.

01:16:37.090 --> 01:16:37.950
So, in other words,

01:16:37.950 --> 01:16:39.900
doing a particular pattern
of breathing allowed

01:16:39.900 --> 01:16:42.370
an anti-inflammatory
cytokine to be turned on,

01:16:42.370 --> 01:16:45.440
whereas that was not
the case in the subjects

01:16:45.440 --> 01:16:49.890
that did not do this
particular breathing protocol.

01:16:49.890 --> 01:16:51.420
And they discovered that levels

01:16:51.420 --> 01:16:56.420
of proinflammatory TNF-alpha,
tumor necrosis factor alpha,

01:16:56.530 --> 01:16:59.470
IL-6, interleukin-6 and interleukin-8,

01:16:59.470 --> 01:17:01.290
which you should all be familiar with now,

01:17:01.290 --> 01:17:04.340
as proinflammatory cytokines were lower

01:17:04.340 --> 01:17:05.640
in the intervention group.

01:17:06.520 --> 01:17:07.800
Whereas these IL-10 levels

01:17:07.800 --> 01:17:09.550
that are anti-inflammatory went up.

01:17:10.740 --> 01:17:13.200
Finally, flu-like symptoms were lower

01:17:13.200 --> 01:17:14.530
in the intervention group.

01:17:14.530 --> 01:17:16.770
So this is an amazing finding, right?

01:17:16.770 --> 01:17:18.033
These are human subjects.

01:17:19.208 --> 01:17:21.330
One group of subjects is
doing this breathing protocol.

01:17:21.330 --> 01:17:24.420
The other group of subjects
is just meditating.

01:17:24.420 --> 01:17:28.560
Both sets of subjects have
been injected with E. coli.

01:17:28.560 --> 01:17:31.550
So, you know everyone's
getting the same amount

01:17:31.550 --> 01:17:33.510
placed into their system.

01:17:33.510 --> 01:17:35.760
This is very, very interesting.

01:17:35.760 --> 01:17:38.990
And it leads to the question
that every good scientist,

01:17:38.990 --> 01:17:41.310
two year old or health
information seeker asks,

01:17:41.310 --> 01:17:42.990
which is why?

01:17:42.990 --> 01:17:43.823
How?

01:17:43.823 --> 01:17:44.810
How in the world does this work?

01:17:44.810 --> 01:17:45.970
Why does this work?

01:17:45.970 --> 01:17:49.760
Well to make a long story shortish,

01:17:49.760 --> 01:17:52.030
because I am going to go into depth here,

01:17:52.030 --> 01:17:54.860
the reason it works is
because the sympathetic

01:17:54.860 --> 01:17:59.380
nervous system, the so-called stress part

01:17:59.380 --> 01:18:01.517
of our nervous system, it's
not really called that,

01:18:01.517 --> 01:18:04.170
but the part of our nervous
system that triggers stress

01:18:04.170 --> 01:18:07.473
from mild stress, to severe
stress, even to panic,

01:18:08.700 --> 01:18:11.370
causes the release of
adrenaline and epinephrin

01:18:11.370 --> 01:18:13.060
in the brain and body.

01:18:13.060 --> 01:18:15.300
And under normal circumstances,

01:18:15.300 --> 01:18:18.530
when we have some sort
of invading infection,

01:18:18.530 --> 01:18:20.980
our body is able to push back on that,

01:18:20.980 --> 01:18:23.950
to resist it by engaging
the stress response.

01:18:23.950 --> 01:18:27.980
So what's happening here is
there's a behavioral protocol

01:18:27.980 --> 01:18:30.180
involving the nervous
system, 'cause all behaviors

01:18:30.180 --> 01:18:32.420
are generated from the
nervous system of course.

01:18:32.420 --> 01:18:36.220
A behavioral protocol that
people are deliberately employing

01:18:36.220 --> 01:18:39.830
that allows them to activate
the sympathetic nervous system,

01:18:39.830 --> 01:18:43.610
which in turn allows them to
activate the normal pathways

01:18:43.610 --> 01:18:47.510
by which immune system
function is enhanced.

01:18:47.510 --> 01:18:48.370
Okay?

01:18:48.370 --> 01:18:51.300
Now, the reason I'm
underscoring this is that

01:18:51.300 --> 01:18:54.570
the common interpretation of
this study is that somehow

01:18:54.570 --> 01:18:57.900
it blocks the normal immune response,

01:18:57.900 --> 01:18:59.780
but that's not really
what's happening here.

01:18:59.780 --> 01:19:03.540
Yes, there's a reduction
in inflammatory cytokines

01:19:03.540 --> 01:19:06.410
and there's an increase in
anti-inflammatory cytokines,

01:19:06.410 --> 01:19:08.340
but that's not really the same thing

01:19:08.340 --> 01:19:10.600
as blocking the immune response.

01:19:10.600 --> 01:19:13.330
This could just as easily
be viewed as enhancing

01:19:13.330 --> 01:19:16.290
the immune response and
combating the intruder,

01:19:16.290 --> 01:19:18.120
in this case, E. coli.

01:19:18.120 --> 01:19:21.960
So, let's parse this study
a little bit more closely.

01:19:21.960 --> 01:19:24.910
First of all, what is this
magical pattern of breathing?

01:19:24.910 --> 01:19:26.340
Some of you may recognize this

01:19:26.340 --> 01:19:28.200
as so-called Wim Hof breathing.

01:19:28.200 --> 01:19:29.830
Wim, of course the Dutchman.

01:19:29.830 --> 01:19:31.470
I think his occupation online used to be

01:19:31.470 --> 01:19:34.090
listed as daredevil, believe
it or not, on Wikipedia.

01:19:34.090 --> 01:19:36.743
That's a pretty cool occupation.

01:19:37.590 --> 01:19:42.590
Wim is best known for his
activities with cold exposure,

01:19:42.680 --> 01:19:45.000
he holds multiple world records for that,

01:19:45.000 --> 01:19:48.510
swimming under icebergs
and other incredible feats,

01:19:48.510 --> 01:19:51.070
that you definitely
don't want to try unless

01:19:51.070 --> 01:19:52.760
you're extremely skilled and really know

01:19:52.760 --> 01:19:54.750
what you're doing, as he does,

01:19:54.750 --> 01:19:56.977
but also for the use of breath work.

01:19:56.977 --> 01:20:00.430
The breathing that is
so-called Wim Hof breathing

01:20:00.430 --> 01:20:02.370
is very similar, not exactly the same,

01:20:02.370 --> 01:20:05.410
but very similar to Tummo breathing,

01:20:05.410 --> 01:20:07.420
as it's been described historically.

01:20:07.420 --> 01:20:09.740
In the science and physiology community

01:20:09.740 --> 01:20:12.550
and in my laboratory, 'cause
I run a university laboratory,

01:20:12.550 --> 01:20:14.670
we refer to it as cyclic hyperventilation,

01:20:14.670 --> 01:20:17.950
which just means repeated
deep breaths in and out.

01:20:17.950 --> 01:20:19.350
And then there are these retentions.

01:20:19.350 --> 01:20:23.130
So, because I'm here
in the hot seat anyway,

01:20:23.130 --> 01:20:24.910
I might as well demonstrate it for you

01:20:24.910 --> 01:20:26.160
so you know what this looks like.

01:20:26.160 --> 01:20:29.360
There are variations on
this, so with respect to Wim,

01:20:29.360 --> 01:20:31.120
with respect to Tummo practitioners,

01:20:31.120 --> 01:20:34.150
with respect to the cyclic
hyperventilators everywhere,

01:20:34.150 --> 01:20:36.020
this is one general theme of it.

01:20:36.020 --> 01:20:40.420
It involves 20 to 30 deep inhales

01:20:40.420 --> 01:20:42.860
and then exhales through the mouth,

01:20:42.860 --> 01:20:46.570
followed by a exhale of all one's air

01:20:46.570 --> 01:20:49.820
and a breath hold, that's the retention.

01:20:49.820 --> 01:20:53.330
And then at some point,
15 to 60 seconds later,

01:20:53.330 --> 01:20:55.490
repeating the 25 or 30 breaths.

01:20:55.490 --> 01:20:59.050
And then again, a breath
hold with lungs empty.

01:20:59.050 --> 01:21:00.490
There are variations on this,

01:21:00.490 --> 01:21:04.490
but in our laboratory and
in this particular study,

01:21:04.490 --> 01:21:05.760
it looks something like this.

01:21:05.760 --> 01:21:07.420
Okay, I'm not going to do
the whole thing right now,

01:21:07.420 --> 01:21:09.156
but it goes something like this.

01:21:09.156 --> 01:21:12.656
[Andrew deeply breathing]

01:21:17.870 --> 01:21:20.970
Okay, so let's assume I
did that for 30 breaths.

01:21:20.970 --> 01:21:23.850
I can already feel myself
perspiring a little bit.

01:21:23.850 --> 01:21:26.270
You're heating up, that's
the release of adrenaline.

01:21:26.270 --> 01:21:27.590
It's caused by that breathing pattern,

01:21:27.590 --> 01:21:29.010
and then exhaling all of one's air,

01:21:29.010 --> 01:21:30.945
no speaking in between like I'm doing.

01:21:30.945 --> 01:21:34.362
[Andrew deeply exhaling]

01:21:36.030 --> 01:21:39.420
And then sitting lungs empty
until one feels the impulse

01:21:39.420 --> 01:21:42.150
to breathe and then
repeating for several rounds,

01:21:42.150 --> 01:21:43.770
two or three or even four rounds.

01:21:43.770 --> 01:21:46.790
Now some people will also
introduce a big inhale

01:21:46.790 --> 01:21:48.490
and breath hold at the end

01:21:48.490 --> 01:21:51.280
and find that indeed they can
hold their breath much longer

01:21:51.280 --> 01:21:53.030
than they normally would be able to.

01:21:53.030 --> 01:21:56.630
Because the trigger to
breathe is normally activated

01:21:56.630 --> 01:21:59.700
by increases in carbon
dioxide in our blood.

01:21:59.700 --> 01:22:01.580
We have neurons in our brain stem

01:22:01.580 --> 01:22:04.270
and in our various regions
of our brain, actually,

01:22:04.270 --> 01:22:07.230
that respond to when
carbon dioxide is too high

01:22:07.230 --> 01:22:08.740
and trigger the reflex to breathe.

01:22:08.740 --> 01:22:10.980
But when we exhale deeply,

01:22:10.980 --> 01:22:12.860
we blow off a lot of carbon dioxide

01:22:12.860 --> 01:22:15.860
so we don't feel that impulse
to breathe come quite as soon.

01:22:17.900 --> 01:22:21.060
Basically this study
looked at people doing

01:22:21.060 --> 01:22:24.440
these cyclic hyperventilation
with retention,

01:22:24.440 --> 01:22:26.740
25 or 30 breaths, then the retention,

01:22:26.740 --> 01:22:28.390
25 or 30 breaths, then retention,

01:22:28.390 --> 01:22:30.210
25 or 30 breaths, then the retention.

01:22:30.210 --> 01:22:33.480
So, three rounds of 25 to 30
breaths followed by exhale,

01:22:33.480 --> 01:22:37.210
hold in between of various duration.

01:22:37.210 --> 01:22:40.960
But in general, 15 to
60 seconds is typical.

01:22:40.960 --> 01:22:43.440
What happened physiologically?

01:22:43.440 --> 01:22:46.300
This is one of the
reasons I like this study.

01:22:46.300 --> 01:22:47.810
What happened physiologically?

01:22:47.810 --> 01:22:49.520
Well, a couple of things.

01:22:49.520 --> 01:22:52.770
Of course, blood oxygenation drops.

01:22:52.770 --> 01:22:55.410
You would expect that
based on hyperventilation

01:22:55.410 --> 01:22:56.870
and especially based on the exhale

01:22:56.870 --> 01:22:58.140
of so much carbon dioxide.

01:22:58.140 --> 01:22:59.240
We could explain why that is,

01:22:59.240 --> 01:23:03.570
but blood levels of oxygen drop.

01:23:03.570 --> 01:23:08.570
The pH, the alkalinity
of the body goes way up.

01:23:09.200 --> 01:23:10.120
This is very interesting.

01:23:10.120 --> 01:23:11.430
If you look up this paper,

01:23:11.430 --> 01:23:14.730
you can look at Figure One,
Panel C, the pH goes way up.

01:23:14.730 --> 01:23:15.840
People become alkaline.

01:23:15.840 --> 01:23:18.270
You've heard before of alkaline water.

01:23:18.270 --> 01:23:19.103
I hate to say this,

01:23:19.103 --> 01:23:20.610
I'll probably lose some friends for this,

01:23:20.610 --> 01:23:24.140
but yeah, don't waste your money
on drinking alkaline water.

01:23:24.140 --> 01:23:27.430
You can't really shift the
alkalinity of your body.

01:23:27.430 --> 01:23:30.340
There are cases where some
compartment in your body

01:23:30.340 --> 01:23:31.950
needs to be more alkaline than the rest.

01:23:31.950 --> 01:23:34.530
Your gut is a different
alkalinity than other areas

01:23:34.530 --> 01:23:38.310
of your body, et cetera, but
ingesting high alkaline water

01:23:38.310 --> 01:23:40.410
isn't going to shift
your overall alkalinity.

01:23:41.320 --> 01:23:43.150
If someone can send me a quality reference

01:23:43.150 --> 01:23:45.400
that shows different than I'm happy

01:23:45.400 --> 01:23:46.450
to revise that statement.

01:23:46.450 --> 01:23:49.760
But in any case, doing
that pattern of breathing

01:23:49.760 --> 01:23:52.540
that I just described
greatly increases the pH.

01:23:52.540 --> 01:23:54.490
Greatly, I should say,
it doesn't send it off

01:23:54.490 --> 01:23:55.360
into dangerous levels.

01:23:55.360 --> 01:23:57.440
It takes it from 7.4 to 7.6,

01:23:57.440 --> 01:24:01.260
which is a significant
increase in alkalinity.

01:24:01.260 --> 01:24:04.630
So, as pH levels, for those
you remember high school

01:24:04.630 --> 01:24:08.750
or college chemistry, as the
numbers on the pH go down,

01:24:08.750 --> 01:24:10.180
you're becoming more acidic,

01:24:10.180 --> 01:24:12.680
as they go up, you're
becoming more alkaline,

01:24:12.680 --> 01:24:14.110
okay or more basic.

01:24:14.110 --> 01:24:17.870
So, these subjects went from 7.4 to 7.6

01:24:17.870 --> 01:24:18.920
during the breathing,

01:24:18.920 --> 01:24:20.700
and then afterwards it returned to normal.

01:24:20.700 --> 01:24:23.260
But that shift in alkalinity is thought

01:24:23.260 --> 01:24:24.950
to be important here.

01:24:24.950 --> 01:24:25.900
So, what's going on here?

01:24:25.900 --> 01:24:30.900
How is the breathing
leading to the shifts in...

01:24:31.690 --> 01:24:35.070
Or I should say reduction
in inflammatory cytokines

01:24:35.070 --> 01:24:38.760
and an increase in the liberation

01:24:38.760 --> 01:24:41.240
of these anti-inflammatory cytokines.

01:24:41.240 --> 01:24:43.450
Well, the authors make some good arguments

01:24:43.450 --> 01:24:47.780
as to why it's not the shift in pH per se,

01:24:47.780 --> 01:24:52.030
or the shift in carbon
dioxide levels in the blood,

01:24:52.030 --> 01:24:54.750
but rather it's the release of epinephrin.

01:24:55.858 --> 01:24:57.740
And there's some good reason
to believe why that's the case.

01:24:57.740 --> 01:24:59.180
It's beyond the scope of this discussion,

01:24:59.180 --> 01:25:02.290
but that it's actually
the release of epinephrin,

01:25:02.290 --> 01:25:05.930
AKA adrenaline, that's
causing this reduction

01:25:05.930 --> 01:25:07.170
in inflammation.

01:25:07.170 --> 01:25:11.660
And that's actually supported by something

01:25:11.660 --> 01:25:13.390
that you've probably experienced before,

01:25:13.390 --> 01:25:15.190
which is if you've ever
worked, worked, worked, worked,

01:25:15.190 --> 01:25:17.490
worked really hard, or
you've been a caretaker

01:25:17.490 --> 01:25:20.120
for somebody else or studying for exams,

01:25:20.120 --> 01:25:21.560
and people around you are getting sick

01:25:21.560 --> 01:25:23.690
and you're just powering through it

01:25:23.690 --> 01:25:24.670
and you're not getting sick,

01:25:24.670 --> 01:25:27.320
but then you stop, you
turn in your final exam,

01:25:27.320 --> 01:25:29.910
you stopped taking care of somebody else,

01:25:29.910 --> 01:25:32.350
or you finally stop and
rest or you go on vacation,

01:25:32.350 --> 01:25:34.070
and then you get sick.

01:25:34.070 --> 01:25:38.870
Well, you've just experienced
the effect that adrenaline,

01:25:38.870 --> 01:25:42.040
epinephrin can have in
activating your immune system

01:25:42.040 --> 01:25:44.040
by way of the nervous system,

01:25:44.040 --> 01:25:47.710
in order to keep fighting
and combating infection.

01:25:47.710 --> 01:25:49.470
And that brings us to a larger theme,

01:25:49.470 --> 01:25:52.980
which is that stress and
combating infection or a wound

01:25:52.980 --> 01:25:56.490
is not one unique system.

01:25:56.490 --> 01:25:58.210
It's the same stress system that you use

01:25:58.210 --> 01:26:00.110
to combat psychological stress.

01:26:00.110 --> 01:26:01.830
So when you're very, very stressed,

01:26:01.830 --> 01:26:03.670
at least in the short term,

01:26:03.670 --> 01:26:06.670
because you release so much
adrenaline and epinephrin,

01:26:06.670 --> 01:26:09.340
you're actually better
able to combat infections

01:26:09.340 --> 01:26:10.517
and you reduce inflammation

01:26:10.517 --> 01:26:12.620
and the whole feeling
lousy response, right?

01:26:12.620 --> 01:26:14.810
Remember reduced flu-like symptoms here.

01:26:14.810 --> 01:26:18.110
So this pattern of breathing
is actually a very useful tool.

01:26:18.110 --> 01:26:20.970
And I confess, I use this
pattern of breathing anytime

01:26:20.970 --> 01:26:23.790
I am at the initial stages
of getting some sort of bug.

01:26:23.790 --> 01:26:26.440
If I feel like I've been
running myself ragged,

01:26:26.440 --> 01:26:28.470
or if I somehow, for whatever reason,

01:26:28.470 --> 01:26:29.750
have a tickle in my throat,

01:26:29.750 --> 01:26:31.930
or I have that kind of
sensation in my nose,

01:26:31.930 --> 01:26:35.330
like I might've caught a bug of some sort,

01:26:35.330 --> 01:26:37.780
I will do this pattern of breathing.

01:26:37.780 --> 01:26:39.330
I've been doing it consistently,

01:26:39.330 --> 01:26:41.713
gosh, for the last four years or more.

01:26:42.722 --> 01:26:45.190
Now this is just anecdotal reports,

01:26:45.190 --> 01:26:49.240
but I find that it allows
me indeed to either

01:26:49.240 --> 01:26:51.750
have those early symptoms disappear,

01:26:51.750 --> 01:26:54.560
or it allows me to just
kind of push through

01:26:54.560 --> 01:26:55.800
and harder, longer.

01:26:55.800 --> 01:26:59.310
I don't suggest people
continue to push through

01:26:59.310 --> 01:27:00.610
exposure to infections.

01:27:00.610 --> 01:27:03.120
Obviously you don't want
to infect other people,

01:27:03.120 --> 01:27:06.700
nor do you want to crash and
suddenly get a massive illness

01:27:06.700 --> 01:27:09.130
of some sort because you
stopped doing this breathing.

01:27:09.130 --> 01:27:10.850
But I do think it's a useful tool.

01:27:10.850 --> 01:27:14.730
It's a purely behavioral
intervention that has been shown

01:27:14.730 --> 01:27:17.830
here and now there are
additional studies on the way,

01:27:17.830 --> 01:27:21.310
to enhance the function
of your immune system

01:27:21.310 --> 01:27:22.740
and to reduce inflammation.

01:27:22.740 --> 01:27:26.100
And this is to me, one of
the most concrete examples

01:27:26.100 --> 01:27:31.100
of a zero cost tool that
bridges the activation

01:27:31.240 --> 01:27:33.880
of the nervous system through breathing

01:27:33.880 --> 01:27:38.200
with the immune system by
way of releasing adrenaline

01:27:38.200 --> 01:27:41.710
and thereby reducing the terrible effects

01:27:41.710 --> 01:27:46.090
or feelings of lousiness
from, in this case,

01:27:46.090 --> 01:27:48.050
an E. coli infection.

01:27:48.050 --> 01:27:52.270
Now, I'd like to focus on a
couple of important points

01:27:52.270 --> 01:27:55.820
that I haven't heard
discussed broadly elsewhere,

01:27:55.820 --> 01:27:58.670
which is that the hyperventilation

01:27:58.670 --> 01:28:01.680
and the breath retention
are both important.

01:28:01.680 --> 01:28:06.680
So you can't simply
hyperventilate to get this effect

01:28:06.740 --> 01:28:09.230
at the level of epinephrin release

01:28:09.230 --> 01:28:11.880
and reduction in inflammatory cytokines.

01:28:11.880 --> 01:28:15.260
It's been shown before that
the hyperventilation phase

01:28:15.260 --> 01:28:19.940
and the hypoxia, which is
a low oxygen saturation

01:28:19.940 --> 01:28:22.030
due to the breath retention,

01:28:22.030 --> 01:28:26.120
they both combine to increase
epinephrin adrenaline levels.

01:28:26.120 --> 01:28:30.040
So, you have to do the 25 or 30 breaths,

01:28:30.040 --> 01:28:31.210
and then the retention.

01:28:31.210 --> 01:28:33.080
25 or 30 breaths then the retention,

01:28:33.080 --> 01:28:34.790
meaning that the exhale
with the breath hold,

01:28:34.790 --> 01:28:36.750
in order to get the full effect.

01:28:36.750 --> 01:28:39.820
I'd also want to provide a
critical cautionary note.

01:28:39.820 --> 01:28:43.730
Don't do this anywhere near
water or while driving a car.

01:28:43.730 --> 01:28:45.610
These things might seem kind of obvious,

01:28:45.610 --> 01:28:49.730
but obviously in the off
chance that you black out

01:28:49.730 --> 01:28:51.300
or something like that,
it could be disastrous.

01:28:51.300 --> 01:28:52.980
So, please be careful.

01:28:52.980 --> 01:28:56.600
And again, don't try and
push the breath hold.

01:28:56.600 --> 01:28:58.960
The moment you feel the impulse
to breathe, just breathe.

01:28:58.960 --> 01:29:02.420
And it did seem that the three
rounds of 25 to 30 breaths

01:29:04.592 --> 01:29:06.630
with breath hold retentions in between

01:29:06.630 --> 01:29:08.550
was the ideal protocol.

01:29:08.550 --> 01:29:11.630
There's one last very
interesting feature of this study

01:29:11.630 --> 01:29:12.970
that I want to emphasize.

01:29:12.970 --> 01:29:16.010
And that was that they
actually measured the so-called

01:29:16.010 --> 01:29:18.040
catecholamine concentrations.

01:29:18.040 --> 01:29:19.720
Catecholamines are things like dopamine,

01:29:19.720 --> 01:29:22.000
epinephrin, norepinephrine.

01:29:22.000 --> 01:29:25.830
These are chemicals in your
nervous system and body

01:29:25.830 --> 01:29:29.380
that promote states of
alertness, dopamine, of course,

01:29:29.380 --> 01:29:32.760
part of the reward and
motivation pathways.

01:29:32.760 --> 01:29:36.150
They explored the levels of
these molecules in blood,

01:29:36.150 --> 01:29:41.150
in plasma during and after
this breathing protocol.

01:29:41.180 --> 01:29:43.220
And it was interesting,
as I mentioned before,

01:29:43.220 --> 01:29:45.540
epinephrin showed robust
increases compared

01:29:45.540 --> 01:29:46.550
to the control group,

01:29:46.550 --> 01:29:49.642
norepinephrine, significant
increases occurred

01:29:49.642 --> 01:29:51.103
in the breathing group,

01:29:52.354 --> 01:29:55.180
in the cyclic hyperventilation
retention breathing group,

01:29:55.180 --> 01:29:57.930
of course, but less so.

01:29:57.930 --> 01:30:01.630
And dopamine levels
actually dropped somewhat.

01:30:01.630 --> 01:30:04.910
But this is very interesting
because there's a new

01:30:04.910 --> 01:30:09.480
and emerging literature largely from Asya,

01:30:09.480 --> 01:30:13.430
A-Y-S-A Rolls' lab in Israel.

01:30:13.430 --> 01:30:18.430
What her laboratory has shown
is that motivational state

01:30:18.710 --> 01:30:23.710
and mindset has a powerful
impact on various aspects

01:30:24.430 --> 01:30:26.010
of the immune system
that were thought to be

01:30:26.010 --> 01:30:29.430
independent of the brain
and mind and thinking.

01:30:29.430 --> 01:30:32.890
So this brings us back to
something that we discussed

01:30:32.890 --> 01:30:34.270
at the very beginning of this episode,

01:30:34.270 --> 01:30:37.190
which is that 20, 30 years ago,

01:30:37.190 --> 01:30:39.460
the idea that you could
heal the body with the mind

01:30:39.460 --> 01:30:41.820
was considered kind of quackery.

01:30:41.820 --> 01:30:45.350
I think that there was an
intervening period up until now

01:30:45.350 --> 01:30:48.120
where people might've said,
"sure, if you're stressed out,

01:30:48.120 --> 01:30:49.220
it's going to make things worse."

01:30:49.220 --> 01:30:50.950
I mean, I think everyone
agrees that stress

01:30:50.950 --> 01:30:54.300
makes every thing worse at some level,

01:30:54.300 --> 01:30:56.640
outcomes to neurodegeneration,

01:30:56.640 --> 01:31:00.530
performance in a physical
endeavors and mental endeavors.

01:31:00.530 --> 01:31:04.380
If stress is too high for too long

01:31:04.380 --> 01:31:07.480
people experience different challenges

01:31:07.480 --> 01:31:09.930
and essentially every
major psychiatric disorder,

01:31:09.930 --> 01:31:11.870
everything suffers, but in the short term,

01:31:11.870 --> 01:31:14.290
stress can actually be
beneficial in the ways

01:31:14.290 --> 01:31:15.220
that we just described.

01:31:15.220 --> 01:31:18.260
And stress, if we break it down

01:31:18.260 --> 01:31:20.900
is really a neurochemical state, right?

01:31:20.900 --> 01:31:23.310
It's the release of these catacholamines.

01:31:23.310 --> 01:31:26.760
And what Asya Rolls' laboratory has shown

01:31:26.760 --> 01:31:29.920
is that when the so-called dopamine system

01:31:29.920 --> 01:31:30.870
and at several episodes,

01:31:30.870 --> 01:31:32.760
I described there are
multiple dopamine systems,

01:31:32.760 --> 01:31:35.280
but the so-called
mesolimbic reward pathway

01:31:35.280 --> 01:31:38.830
involving areas like the
nucleus accumbens, et cetera.

01:31:38.830 --> 01:31:43.630
When the reward system that's
associated with dopamine

01:31:43.630 --> 01:31:46.033
and norepinephrine is activated,

01:31:47.270 --> 01:31:50.923
you see incredible effects,
including for instance,

01:31:51.810 --> 01:31:55.970
highly significant reduction
in tumor size in cancers.

01:31:55.970 --> 01:31:57.570
Now, why would that be?

01:31:57.570 --> 01:32:01.850
How is it that mindset,
dopamine and tumors,

01:32:01.850 --> 01:32:03.650
and tumor growth are somehow linked?

01:32:05.000 --> 01:32:06.890
We now know how this
occurs largely through

01:32:06.890 --> 01:32:09.230
the incredible work of
Asya Rolls and others.

01:32:09.230 --> 01:32:13.170
So, now I'd like to turn our
focus to how it is specifically

01:32:13.170 --> 01:32:17.310
that certain mindsets
impact the immune system

01:32:17.310 --> 01:32:19.000
in ways that we can
actually point to specific

01:32:19.000 --> 01:32:22.280
biological pathways and
also specific protocols

01:32:22.280 --> 01:32:23.760
related to mindset.

01:32:23.760 --> 01:32:27.660
I guess a simple way to frame
all this would be to say

01:32:27.660 --> 01:32:30.180
that most of us are
aware that yes, indeed,

01:32:30.180 --> 01:32:32.380
you can worry yourself sick.

01:32:32.380 --> 01:32:35.170
We've been told that, you're
going to worry yourself sick.

01:32:35.170 --> 01:32:37.870
And actually there was a
paper published in "Science,"

01:32:37.870 --> 01:32:39.950
again, one of the top
three journals out there,

01:32:39.950 --> 01:32:43.150
the top three really being
"Nature," "Science," and "Cell."

01:32:43.150 --> 01:32:45.570
And then other of course,
excellent journals exist,

01:32:45.570 --> 01:32:49.480
but this was a paper that came
out in "Science" last year.

01:32:49.480 --> 01:32:53.740
First author is Kataoka, K-A-T-A-O-K-A,

01:32:55.020 --> 01:32:58.530
describing psychogenic stress and fever.

01:32:58.530 --> 01:33:01.400
So this was looking or
asking the question,

01:33:01.400 --> 01:33:05.110
are there areas of the
brain that actually underlie

01:33:05.110 --> 01:33:08.050
this notion that we can
worry ourselves sick?

01:33:08.050 --> 01:33:10.780
And they discovered a new
pathway and they were able to

01:33:10.780 --> 01:33:14.500
both activate this pathway
independent of worry and stress

01:33:14.500 --> 01:33:16.280
and see illness occur,

01:33:16.280 --> 01:33:18.210
and they were able to
inhibit this pathway,

01:33:18.210 --> 01:33:20.270
block activity in this neural pathway

01:33:20.270 --> 01:33:24.930
and prevent psychogenic
fever and the worrying

01:33:24.930 --> 01:33:26.160
of oneself sick.

01:33:26.160 --> 01:33:29.800
So, they were able to do this
in a very controlled way.

01:33:29.800 --> 01:33:31.920
I'll just mention the pathway in case

01:33:31.920 --> 01:33:34.313
you want to look it up in more detail.

01:33:35.390 --> 01:33:37.560
This is a corticolimbic pathway.

01:33:37.560 --> 01:33:41.310
So, just to orient us,
the cortex is more or less

01:33:41.310 --> 01:33:42.760
the outer shell of the brain.

01:33:42.760 --> 01:33:45.390
It's involved in thinking
and sensation and perceptions

01:33:45.390 --> 01:33:48.530
and learning and maintenance
of a lot of memories

01:33:48.530 --> 01:33:49.363
are stored there.

01:33:49.363 --> 01:33:52.790
We all hear that you learn and
remember in the hippocampus,

01:33:52.790 --> 01:33:55.090
that's the initial site
of learning and memory,

01:33:55.090 --> 01:33:56.660
but then that information,
believe it or not,

01:33:56.660 --> 01:33:58.500
is passed off to the
cortex where it's stored

01:33:58.500 --> 01:34:01.890
in kind of a long-term
hard drive type storage.

01:34:01.890 --> 01:34:05.600
So the corticolimbic
pathway is one in which

01:34:05.600 --> 01:34:10.240
your thoughts, your prior
experiences can literally

01:34:10.240 --> 01:34:13.760
in a structure way, feed down
onto the areas of the brain

01:34:13.760 --> 01:34:15.820
that control very basal processes,

01:34:15.820 --> 01:34:17.120
including temperature regulation.

01:34:17.120 --> 01:34:20.340
So this is a corticolimbic
hypothalamic pathway.

01:34:20.340 --> 01:34:21.720
We talked earlier about the hypothalamus

01:34:21.720 --> 01:34:23.560
as controlling temperature
and a lot of sickness

01:34:23.560 --> 01:34:25.190
related behavior, right?

01:34:25.190 --> 01:34:26.860
Remember vagus up to the hypothalamus

01:34:26.860 --> 01:34:29.770
and all the sleep more,
less appetite, fever.

01:34:29.770 --> 01:34:31.450
Okay, that's all in the hypothalamus.

01:34:31.450 --> 01:34:36.450
This is a top-down corticolimbic
hypothalamic pathway,

01:34:36.610 --> 01:34:38.080
and it has a fancy name.

01:34:38.080 --> 01:34:42.900
It's the dorsal peduncular
cortex, dorsal tinea tecta.

01:34:42.900 --> 01:34:44.980
The short of that is the DP/DTT.

01:34:44.980 --> 01:34:46.960
Let's just call it the DP/DTT,

01:34:46.960 --> 01:34:50.180
to the dorsomedial hypothalamus.

01:34:50.180 --> 01:34:51.200
A lot of D's.

01:34:51.200 --> 01:34:52.550
It shouldn't mean anything.

01:34:53.439 --> 01:34:55.200
It doesn't really matter what we call it.

01:34:55.200 --> 01:35:00.200
But what's important is
conceptually it's a pathway

01:35:00.470 --> 01:35:02.440
that originates insights to the brain

01:35:02.440 --> 01:35:04.830
that are associated with thinking,

01:35:04.830 --> 01:35:07.470
with emotion and with prior history,

01:35:07.470 --> 01:35:09.420
and feeds directly into
an area of the brain

01:35:09.420 --> 01:35:11.500
that's involved in basic physiological

01:35:11.500 --> 01:35:13.660
subconsciously controlled processes.

01:35:13.660 --> 01:35:15.340
So, that's incredible, right?

01:35:15.340 --> 01:35:19.040
And it points to a physical
pathway by which the way

01:35:19.040 --> 01:35:21.940
we think about something
changes something core

01:35:21.940 --> 01:35:23.770
about our physiology.

01:35:23.770 --> 01:35:25.710
Now, in some ways that
shouldn't be surprising, right?

01:35:25.710 --> 01:35:27.390
If you think about
something that excites you,

01:35:27.390 --> 01:35:28.850
your heart rate can increase.

01:35:28.850 --> 01:35:30.120
You think about something
that terrifies you,

01:35:30.120 --> 01:35:31.100
your heart rate can increase.

01:35:31.100 --> 01:35:33.610
So the idea that thinking
controls our physiology

01:35:33.610 --> 01:35:38.460
is not a new concept at all,
but somehow human beings,

01:35:38.460 --> 01:35:43.010
we have been challenged with
the idea that we could actually

01:35:43.010 --> 01:35:44.680
think ourselves into being sick.

01:35:44.680 --> 01:35:49.680
But this paper from Kataoka
shows that if you expose

01:35:50.180 --> 01:35:52.323
somebody to a psychological stress,

01:35:53.660 --> 01:35:56.470
you can actually activate this
pathway and create a fever.

01:35:56.470 --> 01:35:57.303
And how do they do that?

01:35:57.303 --> 01:35:59.770
Well, you can do this by exposing subjects

01:35:59.770 --> 01:36:02.960
to a very stressful real event,

01:36:02.960 --> 01:36:05.080
and you cue it through
our associative learning.

01:36:05.080 --> 01:36:07.970
So, maybe, like my PILOT
V5s, which I love so much,

01:36:07.970 --> 01:36:10.300
we could traumatize me to the PILOT V5

01:36:10.300 --> 01:36:11.930
if I had some horrible
experience happen to me

01:36:11.930 --> 01:36:14.510
while I'm looking at and
concentrating on the PILOT V5.

01:36:14.510 --> 01:36:16.030
Then you take away the
horrible experience,

01:36:16.030 --> 01:36:17.007
you give me the PILOT V5,

01:36:17.007 --> 01:36:19.910
and I start to experience
a lot of the symptoms

01:36:19.910 --> 01:36:22.400
associated with that terrible event.

01:36:22.400 --> 01:36:25.920
They were able to do this
using sickness inducing stimuli

01:36:25.920 --> 01:36:26.753
and so forth.

01:36:26.753 --> 01:36:29.320
They did all the various derivations

01:36:29.320 --> 01:36:33.130
and identified this pathway
that when activated,

01:36:33.130 --> 01:36:35.210
even in the absence of
some horrible event,

01:36:35.210 --> 01:36:39.830
could create fever and
illness-like behavior and so forth.

01:36:39.830 --> 01:36:42.580
And if they blocked certain stations

01:36:42.580 --> 01:36:44.590
along this neural pathway,
they could block that effect.

01:36:44.590 --> 01:36:48.360
So this is really concrete
evidence, proof, if you will,

01:36:48.360 --> 01:36:51.320
that there are dedicated
pathways in the mammalian brain,

01:36:51.320 --> 01:36:52.800
your brain and mine,

01:36:52.800 --> 01:36:55.653
that allow us to turn
thoughts into illness.

01:36:56.640 --> 01:36:58.280
That's kind of a depressing idea.

01:36:58.280 --> 01:36:59.550
What about the inverse?

01:36:59.550 --> 01:37:02.290
What about turning thoughts into health?

01:37:02.290 --> 01:37:04.593
Well, that's the work of Asya Rolls.

01:37:05.660 --> 01:37:10.660
They explored the well-established
psychological phenomenon

01:37:11.320 --> 01:37:15.640
that when cancer patients
or very ill people

01:37:15.640 --> 01:37:18.735
or people who are suffering
from very debilitating injuries,

01:37:18.735 --> 01:37:23.735
when people had a
reported a sense of hope,

01:37:23.970 --> 01:37:26.680
their rates of recovery
were much higher, right?

01:37:26.680 --> 01:37:29.690
Sounds very subjective.

01:37:29.690 --> 01:37:32.090
But what is a sense of hope?

01:37:32.090 --> 01:37:34.890
A sense of hope is a sense of the future.

01:37:34.890 --> 01:37:37.010
A sense of the future
is tightly associated

01:37:37.010 --> 01:37:38.670
with the dopamine system.

01:37:38.670 --> 01:37:40.970
Dopamine, again, being
this molecule of reward

01:37:40.970 --> 01:37:42.930
and motivation and movement,

01:37:42.930 --> 01:37:47.930
but movement and motivation are
about things that are beyond

01:37:48.610 --> 01:37:51.440
the confines of our skin
and are about the future.

01:37:51.440 --> 01:37:54.160
And so what they've discovered
and through other studies

01:37:54.160 --> 01:37:57.400
from other groups have
discovered is that stimulation

01:37:57.400 --> 01:37:58.610
of the dopamine pathway,

01:37:58.610 --> 01:38:02.133
either simply by thinking about a future,

01:38:03.130 --> 01:38:04.430
ideally a positive future,

01:38:04.430 --> 01:38:07.110
but thinking about a positive
future leads to activation

01:38:07.110 --> 01:38:09.600
of the so-called mesolimbic reward pathway

01:38:09.600 --> 01:38:11.740
and could reduce the size of tumors,

01:38:11.740 --> 01:38:13.590
could accelerate wound healing,

01:38:13.590 --> 01:38:18.380
could greatly accelerate the
passage from a state of illness

01:38:18.380 --> 01:38:21.240
to a state of health and wellbeing.

01:38:21.240 --> 01:38:24.060
So there are many, many
studies now starting

01:38:24.060 --> 01:38:27.280
to wick out related to this.

01:38:27.280 --> 01:38:30.730
There's also the idea that
augmenting the dopamine system

01:38:30.730 --> 01:38:33.240
can increase the rate of healing.

01:38:33.240 --> 01:38:35.740
And so, there are individuals
out there who opt,

01:38:35.740 --> 01:38:38.860
for instance, to take things
that increase dopamine.

01:38:38.860 --> 01:38:42.260
Now, obviously drugs of abuse
would not be a good idea

01:38:42.260 --> 01:38:44.280
in this context, even though
they increase dopamine,

01:38:44.280 --> 01:38:45.330
they lead to big crashes,

01:38:45.330 --> 01:38:48.030
they have addictive properties, et cetera.

01:38:48.030 --> 01:38:50.050
I've talked before on
this podcast about things

01:38:50.050 --> 01:38:55.050
like L-tyrosine, taking anywhere
from 500 to 750 milligrams

01:38:55.970 --> 01:38:58.290
can increase dopamine because tyrosine

01:38:58.290 --> 01:39:00.140
is a dopamine precursor, of course.

01:39:00.140 --> 01:39:02.100
Things like Mucuna
pruriens, which are L-dopa,

01:39:02.100 --> 01:39:04.230
the immediate precursor to dopamine.

01:39:04.230 --> 01:39:06.530
Some of these will lead
to somewhat of a crash

01:39:07.550 --> 01:39:08.460
in certain individuals.

01:39:08.460 --> 01:39:10.610
Other people tolerate
them a little bit better.

01:39:10.610 --> 01:39:11.860
Again, you have to talk to your doctor,

01:39:11.860 --> 01:39:13.160
you have to figure out
what's right for you.

01:39:13.160 --> 01:39:16.250
If you have bipolar or
mania or schizophrenia,

01:39:16.250 --> 01:39:19.300
these things, I would not
recommend them at all.

01:39:19.300 --> 01:39:20.390
I'm not recommending them at all,

01:39:20.390 --> 01:39:22.640
I'm just mentioning them
for potential exploration

01:39:22.640 --> 01:39:24.230
if it's safe and right for you.

01:39:24.230 --> 01:39:26.200
But the point is this:

01:39:26.200 --> 01:39:30.170
the dopamine system, when
activated can accelerate healing,

01:39:30.170 --> 01:39:34.180
it can accelerate the recovery
from injury of all kinds.

01:39:34.180 --> 01:39:37.470
And that shouldn't come as a mystery

01:39:37.470 --> 01:39:39.490
or surprise result to us.

01:39:39.490 --> 01:39:42.760
It's because this reward
pathway and the fact

01:39:42.760 --> 01:39:45.220
that it's related to a sense of the future

01:39:45.220 --> 01:39:48.430
seems to liberate entire
systems within the body

01:39:48.430 --> 01:39:52.780
that make inflammatory cytokines go down,

01:39:52.780 --> 01:39:55.610
and anti-inflammatory cytokines go up.

01:39:55.610 --> 01:40:00.330
Exactly as was demonstrated
in the beautiful PNAS study

01:40:00.330 --> 01:40:04.030
where breathing, cyclic hyperventilation,

01:40:04.030 --> 01:40:07.630
was used to increase epinephrin,
increase norepinephrine,

01:40:07.630 --> 01:40:10.800
and to augment the catecholamine system.

01:40:10.800 --> 01:40:14.610
So, I think that the bridges
between these studies

01:40:14.610 --> 01:40:15.443
are really relevant.

01:40:15.443 --> 01:40:17.180
In one case, I'm talking about potentially

01:40:17.180 --> 01:40:20.360
taking an over-the-counter
compound to increase dopamine

01:40:20.360 --> 01:40:21.290
to accelerate healing.

01:40:21.290 --> 01:40:24.380
In another case, we're
talking about using breathing.

01:40:24.380 --> 01:40:27.660
There's also the use
of cold water exposure

01:40:27.660 --> 01:40:28.570
to increase dopamine.

01:40:28.570 --> 01:40:30.300
I talked about this several episodes ago,

01:40:30.300 --> 01:40:33.640
but it's been shown that
immersing oneself in cold water

01:40:33.640 --> 01:40:35.010
up to the neck or so.

01:40:35.010 --> 01:40:35.843
How cold?

01:40:35.843 --> 01:40:37.030
Well, it depends on what you can tolerate,

01:40:37.030 --> 01:40:38.310
but uncomfortably cold,

01:40:38.310 --> 01:40:40.210
but not so cold that
you become hypothermic,

01:40:40.210 --> 01:40:42.870
but where it's challenging to get in,

01:40:42.870 --> 01:40:46.280
but you can stay there for
three to 10 minutes or so,

01:40:46.280 --> 01:40:50.120
has been shown to lead
to very significant,

01:40:50.120 --> 01:40:53.820
up to doubling or more of
baseline dopamine levels

01:40:53.820 --> 01:40:56.890
and epinephrin levels that
go on for several hours.

01:40:56.890 --> 01:41:01.230
This may be the basis for why
people will do cold showers

01:41:01.230 --> 01:41:03.110
or ice baths and then get into a sauna.

01:41:03.110 --> 01:41:06.890
So, what's called
cold-heat contrast therapy,

01:41:06.890 --> 01:41:09.330
as a way to augment
these neurotransmitters.

01:41:09.330 --> 01:41:11.210
Today, we've been talking about
how these neurotransmitters

01:41:11.210 --> 01:41:14.950
can be used to enhance the
function of the immune system.

01:41:14.950 --> 01:41:17.870
And so just keep in mind that
anytime you're talking about

01:41:17.870 --> 01:41:19.330
increasing neurotransmitter levels,

01:41:19.330 --> 01:41:22.190
that can be done pharmacologically
through supplementation,

01:41:22.190 --> 01:41:24.560
or the can be done
behaviorally through exposure

01:41:24.560 --> 01:41:26.350
to cold water, for instance,

01:41:26.350 --> 01:41:29.210
or it can be done even
just simply by breathing

01:41:29.210 --> 01:41:30.100
in a particular way,

01:41:30.100 --> 01:41:32.893
cyclic hyperventilation
followed by retention.

01:41:33.930 --> 01:41:36.420
The catacholamines,
noradrenaline, dopamine,

01:41:36.420 --> 01:41:39.780
and norepinephrine are
the bridge of activation

01:41:39.780 --> 01:41:42.380
for the immune system
and the nervous system.

01:41:42.380 --> 01:41:44.490
They are the way that the
nervous system calls out

01:41:44.490 --> 01:41:48.040
to the immune system,
"Aha, we have a problem.

01:41:48.040 --> 01:41:49.290
We need to counter this."

01:41:49.290 --> 01:41:53.050
So you can think of them,
them meaning dopamine,

01:41:53.050 --> 01:41:54.880
epinephrine, and norepinephrine,

01:41:54.880 --> 01:41:59.880
as being able to deploy larger
amounts of immune cells,

01:42:00.270 --> 01:42:02.100
all the types of immune
cells that we talked about

01:42:02.100 --> 01:42:04.120
at the beginning of the episode.

01:42:04.120 --> 01:42:09.080
Okay, so thus far, we've been
discussing how one can prevent

01:42:09.080 --> 01:42:12.720
getting sick or when
one starts to feel ill,

01:42:12.720 --> 01:42:14.710
how one might be able
to shorten the course

01:42:14.710 --> 01:42:17.420
of that infection by
ramping up the activity

01:42:17.420 --> 01:42:18.980
of the immune system.

01:42:18.980 --> 01:42:22.440
But what about when you're
already experiencing symptoms?

01:42:22.440 --> 01:42:25.830
The runny nose, stuffed
up nose, congestion,

01:42:25.830 --> 01:42:27.860
headache, et cetera.

01:42:27.860 --> 01:42:30.410
Well, there are many ways to address that

01:42:30.410 --> 01:42:31.590
at the symptom level.

01:42:31.590 --> 01:42:33.070
You're probably aware of all

01:42:33.070 --> 01:42:35.050
the over the counter medications,

01:42:35.050 --> 01:42:39.130
many of which focus on
the epinephrin system.

01:42:39.130 --> 01:42:43.160
Things that are of the
Sudafed variety prevent

01:42:43.160 --> 01:42:46.060
or reduce congestion because of the way

01:42:46.060 --> 01:42:48.540
that they cause release of epinephrin,

01:42:48.540 --> 01:42:52.190
and some of the effects on
dilating the bronchioles

01:42:52.190 --> 01:42:54.543
and dilating the nasal
passages and so forth.

01:42:56.050 --> 01:42:57.480
I'm not going to speak to whether or not

01:42:57.480 --> 01:42:59.240
those are good or bad choices.

01:42:59.240 --> 01:43:02.160
They do have a couple of
effects that are not so great

01:43:02.160 --> 01:43:05.660
for the course of treating
the underlying cause,

01:43:05.660 --> 01:43:09.150
which are first of all
they can cause dehydration.

01:43:09.150 --> 01:43:10.900
So you have to make sure
that you're hydrating well,

01:43:10.900 --> 01:43:13.580
both fluids and electrolytes,

01:43:13.580 --> 01:43:16.840
and they also can interfere with sleep

01:43:16.840 --> 01:43:20.350
because as I've talked about
in the episodes on sleep,

01:43:20.350 --> 01:43:22.710
one of the hallmarks of
deep sleep and in particular

01:43:22.710 --> 01:43:27.310
REM sleep is that epinephrin,
adrenaline levels are low.

01:43:27.310 --> 01:43:29.840
This is what allows you to have intense,

01:43:29.840 --> 01:43:33.770
often very emotionally-laden
dreams during REM sleep

01:43:33.770 --> 01:43:36.370
and not act those out.

01:43:36.370 --> 01:43:40.140
And low adrenaline,
epinephrin during REM sleep

01:43:40.140 --> 01:43:42.230
is basically a signature,

01:43:42.230 --> 01:43:44.330
a neurochemical signature
of the REM sleep state,

01:43:44.330 --> 01:43:47.560
which is so vital for
emotional and physical repair

01:43:47.560 --> 01:43:48.393
and so forth.

01:43:48.393 --> 01:43:50.490
So, the fact that they can inhibit sleep,

01:43:50.490 --> 01:43:52.560
the fact that can cause dehydration,

01:43:52.560 --> 01:43:54.390
the fact that they can make
people feel kind of lightheaded

01:43:54.390 --> 01:43:57.410
and jittery makes them
not terrific choices

01:43:57.410 --> 01:43:59.040
for a number of people.

01:43:59.040 --> 01:44:01.150
There is an interesting
alternative choice.

01:44:01.150 --> 01:44:04.110
And when I say alternative,
I do mean alternative.

01:44:04.110 --> 01:44:06.660
The choice that I'm
referring to is spirulina,

01:44:06.660 --> 01:44:09.040
which is actually a form of algae.

01:44:09.040 --> 01:44:12.070
Years ago, I think when I
first heard about spirulina,

01:44:12.070 --> 01:44:14.937
it sounded very much of the kind of 1970s,

01:44:14.937 --> 01:44:17.290
80s health food store variety.

01:44:17.290 --> 01:44:19.960
It seemed really kind
of mystical and wacky,

01:44:19.960 --> 01:44:22.450
but actually now there are
some really nice studies

01:44:22.450 --> 01:44:25.240
and some data, and also an
understanding of the mechanism

01:44:25.240 --> 01:44:28.010
by which spirulina can have potent effects

01:44:28.010 --> 01:44:29.930
in reducing what's called rhinitis,

01:44:29.930 --> 01:44:33.440
which is a fancy word for
congestion of the nose

01:44:33.440 --> 01:44:34.820
and an inflammation of the nose.

01:44:34.820 --> 01:44:39.820
Basically, anytime you hear
a word that includes "itis,"

01:44:39.860 --> 01:44:41.850
at least if it's in the
medical or health context,

01:44:41.850 --> 01:44:44.200
it generally means
inflammation of some tissue.

01:44:45.490 --> 01:44:48.650
So rhinitis just being
inflammation of the nasal passages,

01:44:48.650 --> 01:44:50.530
but that's one of the most
uncomfortable symptoms

01:44:50.530 --> 01:44:52.080
of any kind of infection.

01:44:52.080 --> 01:44:54.330
So there are two studies
I'd like to highlight

01:44:54.330 --> 01:44:55.200
just very quickly.

01:44:55.200 --> 01:44:58.220
One is the effects of
spirulina on allergic rhinitis.

01:44:58.220 --> 01:45:00.020
And the other is a clinical comparison

01:45:00.020 --> 01:45:01.970
to the efficacy of spirulina platensis,

01:45:05.360 --> 01:45:06.802
that's a technical name,

01:45:06.802 --> 01:45:10.630
and cetirizine for the
treatment of allergic rhinitis.

01:45:10.630 --> 01:45:13.590
These looked at humans, so
this is not a mouse study,

01:45:13.590 --> 01:45:14.890
this is a study on humans.

01:45:16.210 --> 01:45:18.820
Both sexes, so males and females.

01:45:18.820 --> 01:45:22.376
In one case, looking at 100
plus subjects, 129 subjects.

01:45:22.376 --> 01:45:24.700
The other, 65 subjects, so
decent number of subjects,

01:45:24.700 --> 01:45:27.480
randomized trial, double blind.

01:45:27.480 --> 01:45:32.480
Both cases saw significant
decreases in nasal obstruction,

01:45:33.090 --> 01:45:36.233
improved ability to smell, improved sleep,

01:45:37.430 --> 01:45:42.313
daily working inflammatory
cytokines were reduced as well,

01:45:43.440 --> 01:45:44.460
reduction in nasal itching,

01:45:44.460 --> 01:45:46.340
all the stuff that you'd
like to experience,

01:45:46.340 --> 01:45:49.340
I can imagine, after taking two grams,

01:45:49.340 --> 01:45:52.770
two grams, not milligrams,
but two grams of spirulina.

01:45:52.770 --> 01:45:55.210
Sometimes had to be
taken for a short while

01:45:55.210 --> 01:45:56.760
before the effect kicked in.

01:45:56.760 --> 01:45:59.480
So, that's pretty impressive, I would say,

01:45:59.480 --> 01:46:01.320
but it doesn't really speak to mechanism,

01:46:01.320 --> 01:46:05.240
but in exploring the underlying
mechanisms for spirulina's

01:46:05.240 --> 01:46:08.280
effects on reducing rhinitis,

01:46:08.280 --> 01:46:12.560
it's interesting to find that
spirulina actually can inhibit

01:46:12.560 --> 01:46:15.570
the formation and/or activity of so-called

01:46:15.570 --> 01:46:19.550
histaminergic mast cells,
M-A-S-T, mast cells.

01:46:19.550 --> 01:46:21.620
We haven't talked a lot about mast cells,

01:46:21.620 --> 01:46:23.800
but they are a very interesting cell type

01:46:23.800 --> 01:46:25.610
in the immune response.

01:46:25.610 --> 01:46:29.510
Essentially what they are, are
little packets of histamine.

01:46:29.510 --> 01:46:34.510
And when we have some sort
of injury or irritant rather

01:46:36.970 --> 01:46:40.290
to the skin, so a mosquito
bite, for instance,

01:46:40.290 --> 01:46:42.143
or poison oak or poison ivy,

01:46:43.470 --> 01:46:44.860
something that causes an itch

01:46:44.860 --> 01:46:47.080
or something that causes
inflammation internally,

01:46:47.080 --> 01:46:48.590
doesn't just have to be on the skin,

01:46:48.590 --> 01:46:51.690
these mast are these little
bubbles that contain histamine

01:46:51.690 --> 01:46:53.850
that go to that site [hissing],

01:46:53.850 --> 01:46:56.200
and release their histaminergic contents

01:46:56.200 --> 01:47:00.270
and cause swelling and
inflammation of whatever cells

01:47:00.270 --> 01:47:01.403
are affected locally.

01:47:02.520 --> 01:47:04.530
You might think, well, why
would I want to have a mechanism

01:47:04.530 --> 01:47:06.760
in my body that would cause
swelling and inflammation?

01:47:06.760 --> 01:47:11.140
Ah, well then those cells in
turn send out cytokine signals

01:47:11.140 --> 01:47:15.010
that recruit the very cell
types that we were talking about

01:47:15.010 --> 01:47:17.640
way back at the beginning of the episode,

01:47:17.640 --> 01:47:19.470
the cells that are characteristics

01:47:19.470 --> 01:47:21.730
of the innate immune system that come in,

01:47:21.730 --> 01:47:24.290
the macrophages and the
other types of cells

01:47:24.290 --> 01:47:26.960
that will come in and gobble
up the foreign invaders

01:47:26.960 --> 01:47:29.860
or will help sequester and move away,

01:47:29.860 --> 01:47:34.040
say the poison from a bite
or from whatever irritant.

01:47:34.040 --> 01:47:36.910
Again, it doesn't just have
to be at the skin surface.

01:47:36.910 --> 01:47:40.160
I'm describing an example of
at the skin, for instance,

01:47:40.160 --> 01:47:43.180
if you've ever had hives of any kind,

01:47:43.180 --> 01:47:47.060
that almost certainly involved mast cells.

01:47:47.060 --> 01:47:51.640
So, and when you take an
anti-histamine in order to deal

01:47:51.640 --> 01:47:53.540
with seasonal allergies, for instance,

01:47:56.014 --> 01:47:57.970
you're taking a compound that's reducing

01:47:57.970 --> 01:47:59.690
histamines in mast cells.

01:47:59.690 --> 01:48:02.750
And spirulina has also been
used quite effectively as a way

01:48:02.750 --> 01:48:06.330
to treat seasonal allergies
and some of the symptomatology.

01:48:06.330 --> 01:48:09.100
Equally on par with some
of the major prescription

01:48:09.100 --> 01:48:11.420
and over the counter drugs for that.

01:48:11.420 --> 01:48:15.480
One cautionary note, spirulina
can carry some side effects

01:48:15.480 --> 01:48:19.130
for people that have a genetic mutation

01:48:19.130 --> 01:48:20.350
leading to something called PKU.

01:48:20.350 --> 01:48:21.430
These people know who they are.

01:48:21.430 --> 01:48:24.650
They're very sensitive to phenylalanine.

01:48:24.650 --> 01:48:26.520
These same people cannot drink any sort

01:48:26.520 --> 01:48:30.130
of NutraSweet or diet soda for
reasons that they understand.

01:48:30.130 --> 01:48:31.010
It can be quite dangerous.

01:48:31.010 --> 01:48:33.300
It's a rare genetic
disorder, but nonetheless,

01:48:33.300 --> 01:48:36.420
spirulina can be an
issue for those people.

01:48:36.420 --> 01:48:40.310
For most people, the side effect
profile is pretty minimal.

01:48:40.310 --> 01:48:42.070
And just to be clear, I
don't have any relationship

01:48:42.070 --> 01:48:43.750
to spirulina company or anything.

01:48:43.750 --> 01:48:46.480
I just find it interesting
that there are these compounds

01:48:46.480 --> 01:48:49.080
that sound rather, forgive the phrase,

01:48:49.080 --> 01:48:52.440
but rather new-agey because they come from

01:48:52.440 --> 01:48:54.140
a algae, from a plant.

01:48:54.140 --> 01:48:55.700
But when you look at the
underlying mechanism,

01:48:55.700 --> 01:48:57.010
it makes perfect sense.

01:48:57.010 --> 01:48:59.500
So that's often what we
like to point out here

01:48:59.500 --> 01:49:02.493
is that if there are these
so-called alternative therapies,

01:49:03.330 --> 01:49:05.040
alternative because most
people haven't heard of them,

01:49:05.040 --> 01:49:08.040
it's always nice if they map
to a specific logical mechanism

01:49:08.040 --> 01:49:09.880
and framework by which
that compound would work,

01:49:09.880 --> 01:49:11.527
as opposed to just some anecdote of,

01:49:11.527 --> 01:49:13.520
"Oh, I hear spirulina
is great for allergies."

01:49:13.520 --> 01:49:15.900
Well, now we know why,
it inhibits mast cells

01:49:15.900 --> 01:49:18.810
and histaminergic mast
cells in particular.

01:49:18.810 --> 01:49:22.380
Earlier, I mentioned a new
and very exciting study

01:49:22.380 --> 01:49:24.570
published as a full article in "Nature."

01:49:24.570 --> 01:49:28.490
Full article means that
it is a major finding.

01:49:28.490 --> 01:49:30.710
At the journal, "Nature,"
they have letters,

01:49:30.710 --> 01:49:32.120
which are important findings.

01:49:32.120 --> 01:49:34.630
They're still very high
stringency for getting

01:49:34.630 --> 01:49:36.610
a letter in "Nature" published.

01:49:36.610 --> 01:49:40.400
But the full articles, generally
there's only one or two

01:49:40.400 --> 01:49:44.730
per issue in the weekly
edition of "Nature."

01:49:44.730 --> 01:49:47.770
And just last week, there
was a very exciting article

01:49:47.770 --> 01:49:51.420
published from Qiufu Ma's lab
at Harvard Medical School.

01:49:51.420 --> 01:49:53.360
Qiufu I've known for a number of years.

01:49:53.360 --> 01:49:55.700
His group has done phenomenal
work on the mechanisms

01:49:55.700 --> 01:49:58.980
of itch and pain and discovering
some of the receptors

01:49:58.980 --> 01:50:00.370
and pathways for itch and pain.

01:50:00.370 --> 01:50:02.440
And more recently they've been exploring

01:50:02.440 --> 01:50:05.660
